00:00:20.902 --> 00:00:23.110
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: All
right, let's jump ahead here.

00:00:26.710 --> 00:00:32.259
Let me talk a little bit about
manufacturing in general,

00:00:32.259 --> 00:00:34.990
and the competitive challenge
for US manufacturing.

00:00:34.990 --> 00:00:41.830
So the 1990s, manufacturing
was 30% of US economic growth.

00:00:41.830 --> 00:00:46.720
And it had manufacturing at
two times the productivity

00:00:46.720 --> 00:00:48.040
level of the services sector.

00:00:48.040 --> 00:00:50.890
So manufacturing
almost invariably

00:00:50.890 --> 00:00:55.800
has a much higher productivity
level than a services sector.

00:00:55.800 --> 00:00:58.060
US is 80% services.

00:00:58.060 --> 00:01:00.760
So if you really want a
high productivity growth,

00:01:00.760 --> 00:01:04.750
manufacturing is a
way of scaling goods

00:01:04.750 --> 00:01:06.623
and affect product quickly.

00:01:06.623 --> 00:01:09.040
Service sector scale much more
slowly because they're more

00:01:09.040 --> 00:01:11.440
face-to-face.

00:01:11.440 --> 00:01:13.780
So you probably want a
significant component

00:01:13.780 --> 00:01:18.730
of your economy in something
that scales and it introduces

00:01:18.730 --> 00:01:20.170
productivity effectively.

00:01:20.170 --> 00:01:21.910
And that tends to
be manufacturing.

00:01:21.910 --> 00:01:24.040
So manufacturing is also
traditionally higher

00:01:24.040 --> 00:01:25.510
paying jobs.

00:01:25.510 --> 00:01:29.380
In 2001, they were 23% higher
than the services sector.

00:01:29.380 --> 00:01:31.660
The ratio is not all
that different today.

00:01:35.860 --> 00:01:39.520
Manufacturing is an important
part of the US economy.

00:01:39.520 --> 00:01:49.605
It's about 12% of GDP, and it
funds 2/3 of industrial R&D.

00:01:49.605 --> 00:01:53.420
It funds 3/4 of industrial
research and development,

00:01:53.420 --> 00:01:57.090
and about 2/3 of overall US R&D.

00:01:57.090 --> 00:02:04.330
And manufacturing firms account
for a greater percentage

00:02:04.330 --> 00:02:08.509
of real GDP than all these
other kinds of sectors.

00:02:08.509 --> 00:02:10.810
So it remains a very
significant player,

00:02:10.810 --> 00:02:14.440
but it's also a big enabler
for the other sectors.

00:02:14.440 --> 00:02:16.780
So manufacturing jobs--
and there's a lot of debate

00:02:16.780 --> 00:02:19.240
as to what the multiplier is--

00:02:19.240 --> 00:02:23.020
differs from sector to sector,
but it is the biggest job

00:02:23.020 --> 00:02:24.430
multiplier in our economy.

00:02:24.430 --> 00:02:26.710
In other words, a
manufacturing job

00:02:26.710 --> 00:02:28.888
tends to create
additional employment

00:02:28.888 --> 00:02:30.430
in the kind of value
chains that it's

00:02:30.430 --> 00:02:33.220
connected with in the
services sector, and supplier

00:02:33.220 --> 00:02:36.790
sector, and resource sectors.

00:02:36.790 --> 00:02:46.120
So the US has been running
frightening trade deficits

00:02:46.120 --> 00:02:50.660
in manufactured goods for a
significant period of time.

00:02:50.660 --> 00:02:54.560
And it began under
President Nixon,

00:02:54.560 --> 00:02:59.915
and has continued
to grow since then.

00:02:59.915 --> 00:03:04.780
The most problematic
number is the trade deficit

00:03:04.780 --> 00:03:07.750
the US has in advanced
manufacturing goods--

00:03:07.750 --> 00:03:11.590
in other words, complex
high-value goods.

00:03:11.590 --> 00:03:15.070
The US is running $100 billion
trade deficit in those goods.

00:03:15.070 --> 00:03:19.780
So the theory that we'd
seed low-end production

00:03:19.780 --> 00:03:22.862
but make it up by retaining
high-end production,

00:03:22.862 --> 00:03:23.570
it's not working.

00:03:27.080 --> 00:03:32.480
And manufacturing job loss
has a pretty painful history.

00:03:32.480 --> 00:03:38.060
2.7 million jobs were lost in
that 2000 and 2003 recession--

00:03:38.060 --> 00:03:42.290
5.8 million jobs
between 2000 and 2010,

00:03:42.290 --> 00:03:45.890
the majority of those focused
on that 2008 recession.

00:03:45.890 --> 00:03:49.790
In that 2000 to
2010 timetable, we

00:03:49.790 --> 00:03:55.950
shut down about
62,000 factories net.

00:03:55.950 --> 00:04:00.600
The US has been moving its
percentage of manufacturing

00:04:00.600 --> 00:04:02.310
employment ever downward.

00:04:02.310 --> 00:04:05.220
So we're at about
8% of US employment

00:04:05.220 --> 00:04:07.080
is in the manufacturing sector.

00:04:07.080 --> 00:04:08.640
Other countries don't do that.

00:04:08.640 --> 00:04:13.020
So Germany employs about 20% of
its workforce in manufacturing,

00:04:13.020 --> 00:04:18.089
Italy 19%, Japan
22%, South Korea 31%.

00:04:18.089 --> 00:04:20.790
In other words, manufacturing
is a source of higher wages

00:04:20.790 --> 00:04:23.670
and it's a job multiplier.

00:04:23.670 --> 00:04:26.453
You can see some of the
potential competitive

00:04:26.453 --> 00:04:28.620
advantages for retaining a
substantial manufacturing

00:04:28.620 --> 00:04:30.625
sector.

00:04:30.625 --> 00:04:32.250
So those are kind of
background points.

00:04:32.250 --> 00:04:36.660
Let me do a couple
of pieces now.

00:04:36.660 --> 00:04:39.210
I'll do Glenn Fong
and Linsu Kim.

00:04:39.210 --> 00:04:45.700
So Glenn teaches at
Thunderbird in Arizona,

00:04:45.700 --> 00:04:48.855
which is a very fine school
for international business.

00:04:51.450 --> 00:04:56.840
And he wrote a
piece in '98 about

00:04:56.840 --> 00:05:02.610
what was happening in
Japan in that time period.

00:05:02.610 --> 00:05:08.210
So Japan is on a complete
take-off as a leading world

00:05:08.210 --> 00:05:14.930
economy until the 1990
frame, and then it

00:05:14.930 --> 00:05:19.610
misses the IT innovation
wave, as we discussed earlier.

00:05:19.610 --> 00:05:25.670
And it starts to have to
reorganize and rethink

00:05:25.670 --> 00:05:27.740
its innovation system.

00:05:27.740 --> 00:05:31.280
So Glenn argues that
there are essentially

00:05:31.280 --> 00:05:35.780
three historical stages to
Japan's competitive pattern.

00:05:35.780 --> 00:05:39.720
So first, it was the
pursuer after the pioneer--

00:05:39.720 --> 00:05:43.040
the US being the
innovation pioneer--

00:05:43.040 --> 00:05:47.900
then it's a follower right
at the frontier with US,

00:05:47.900 --> 00:05:50.420
and then it becomes a
world-class competitor.

00:05:50.420 --> 00:05:53.600
And he argues that,
as Japan became

00:05:53.600 --> 00:05:56.780
a world-class competitor,
it had to rethink

00:05:56.780 --> 00:05:59.300
its more centralized
organization

00:05:59.300 --> 00:06:00.920
of its innovations.

00:06:00.920 --> 00:06:03.680
So the old thesis about
Japan, Glenn argues,

00:06:03.680 --> 00:06:08.360
is that it was focused on
national industrial performance

00:06:08.360 --> 00:06:11.420
and a corresponding competitive
balance between nations

00:06:11.420 --> 00:06:14.180
based on national
industrial performance.

00:06:14.180 --> 00:06:17.510
And it was set by political
economies really operating

00:06:17.510 --> 00:06:19.880
at the national scale, but
at the governmental scale

00:06:19.880 --> 00:06:22.330
with a strong governmental role.

00:06:22.330 --> 00:06:27.910
But then a more pragmatic
approach has to evolve.

00:06:27.910 --> 00:06:31.900
So MITI, which I
mentioned earlier,

00:06:31.900 --> 00:06:34.270
was the key
organizing institution

00:06:34.270 --> 00:06:36.250
around getting collaboration
between government

00:06:36.250 --> 00:06:41.080
and industry, and setting
industry agendas in Japan.

00:06:41.080 --> 00:06:47.980
In its older period, it would
set technology initiatives

00:06:47.980 --> 00:06:53.030
that were selected by
high-level governmental leaders,

00:06:53.030 --> 00:06:54.550
including at MITI.

00:06:54.550 --> 00:06:57.910
And then in a more
recent period,

00:06:57.910 --> 00:07:00.820
it's had to move towards
technology initiatives that are

00:07:00.820 --> 00:07:03.830
really selected by industry.

00:07:03.830 --> 00:07:07.720
In other words, at the
frontier, the ability

00:07:07.720 --> 00:07:12.130
of government to pick
the technology menu

00:07:12.130 --> 00:07:13.780
becomes more problematic.

00:07:13.780 --> 00:07:16.550
You've got to get that down to
industry decision makers that

00:07:16.550 --> 00:07:19.050
are much closer to markets and
much closer to the innovation

00:07:19.050 --> 00:07:20.470
system itself.

00:07:20.470 --> 00:07:25.960
And that has evolved in Japan,
that high officials just

00:07:25.960 --> 00:07:30.690
can't keep an eye on the rapidly
evolving complex technologies.

00:07:30.690 --> 00:07:33.180
So that's technology
initiatives.

00:07:33.180 --> 00:07:34.830
Then there was
technology targeting.

00:07:34.830 --> 00:07:38.210
In the old period, there was
direct government targeting

00:07:38.210 --> 00:07:41.220
of one or two
specific technologies

00:07:41.220 --> 00:07:44.100
that we're going to be
pursued by the government.

00:07:44.100 --> 00:07:49.650
And the funding was at the
late development stages.

00:07:49.650 --> 00:07:53.700
Government funding was focused
really on advanced prototyping

00:07:53.700 --> 00:07:54.930
and engineering development.

00:07:54.930 --> 00:07:57.070
That's where the government
support was going.

00:07:57.070 --> 00:08:00.540
In the newer period,
Japan shifted

00:08:00.540 --> 00:08:05.070
towards more fundamental
research funding, along

00:08:05.070 --> 00:08:08.910
with it's applied, to put a
broader range of technology

00:08:08.910 --> 00:08:11.670
alternatives onto the table.

00:08:11.670 --> 00:08:13.590
As Glenn characterized
it, it moved

00:08:13.590 --> 00:08:19.370
to a kind of shotgun approach,
not a more narrow rifle shot

00:08:19.370 --> 00:08:20.640
approach.

00:08:20.640 --> 00:08:23.150
And then finally,
industry targeting.

00:08:23.150 --> 00:08:26.460
In the older period,
MITI would actually

00:08:26.460 --> 00:08:28.220
pick winning companies.

00:08:28.220 --> 00:08:31.500
It would decide who's
going to win, designating

00:08:31.500 --> 00:08:34.080
specific companies for funding.

00:08:34.080 --> 00:08:37.830
And it would attempt to
influence corporate mergers

00:08:37.830 --> 00:08:41.230
and consolidations to
develop strong companies.

00:08:41.230 --> 00:08:42.970
So it's intervening
at the company

00:08:42.970 --> 00:08:46.520
stage pretty systematically
at critical areas.

00:08:46.520 --> 00:08:51.490
In the newer period, MITI
became much more collaborative.

00:08:51.490 --> 00:08:54.570
And it's funding a
range of companies

00:08:54.570 --> 00:08:56.550
and a range of
collaboration models,

00:08:56.550 --> 00:09:00.630
not attempting to target
particular surviving firms that

00:09:00.630 --> 00:09:02.370
are winners.

00:09:02.370 --> 00:09:07.170
So in the computing
area, for example,

00:09:07.170 --> 00:09:10.740
MITI goes from funding three
firms over a 30-year period

00:09:10.740 --> 00:09:14.700
to 25 firms at the
end of that period.

00:09:14.700 --> 00:09:17.430
So it's moving
towards a system that

00:09:17.430 --> 00:09:23.340
is less centralized
and more reflective

00:09:23.340 --> 00:09:24.990
of the industry
leadership, and away

00:09:24.990 --> 00:09:28.740
from an interventionist
government role.

00:09:28.740 --> 00:09:29.990
So that's kind of interesting.

00:09:29.990 --> 00:09:37.803
Japan gets to the
innovation frontier

00:09:37.803 --> 00:09:39.470
through a significant
governmental role.

00:09:39.470 --> 00:09:41.590
But when it's at the
frontier and it's truly

00:09:41.590 --> 00:09:43.730
a world-class
competitor, it's got

00:09:43.730 --> 00:09:46.370
to develop a much more
decentralized approach that

00:09:46.370 --> 00:09:49.790
allows ideas to rise
up from that system.

00:09:49.790 --> 00:09:54.590
So that may be an important
organizational model for us

00:09:54.590 --> 00:09:55.248
to consider.

00:09:55.248 --> 00:09:56.790
That organizational
model, of course,

00:09:56.790 --> 00:10:00.560
is more like what the US had on.

00:10:00.560 --> 00:10:04.700
Now, let me put Linsu
Kim into this mix too.

00:10:04.700 --> 00:10:06.500
And his book Imitation
to Innovation

00:10:06.500 --> 00:10:15.950
is a classic in looking
at the amazing evolution

00:10:15.950 --> 00:10:17.042
of Korean economy.

00:10:25.530 --> 00:10:27.690
The thing to understand
about the Korean economy

00:10:27.690 --> 00:10:33.150
is that the country was just
totally destroyed and ruined

00:10:33.150 --> 00:10:35.010
by the Korean War.

00:10:35.010 --> 00:10:38.070
And every inch of
that nation was

00:10:38.070 --> 00:10:43.500
fought over a multi-year period,
and nothing was left standing.

00:10:43.500 --> 00:10:47.280
It's a complete tragedy,
and the population

00:10:47.280 --> 00:10:48.450
is completely disrupted.

00:10:48.450 --> 00:10:53.430
It's forced to move
all about the country.

00:10:53.430 --> 00:10:54.840
Families are disrupted.

00:10:54.840 --> 00:10:57.240
Communities and villages
are completely disrupted.

00:10:57.240 --> 00:11:04.350
It's all thrown together,
and it's truly tragic.

00:11:04.350 --> 00:11:07.170
And yet out of
that tragedy is one

00:11:07.170 --> 00:11:12.900
of the most remarkable
stories of industry scale up

00:11:12.900 --> 00:11:16.050
and growth, and growth
of the country that--

00:11:16.050 --> 00:11:18.330
it's an amazing story.

00:11:18.330 --> 00:11:20.640
And essentially, in
a 30-year period,

00:11:20.640 --> 00:11:24.000
to construct an economy out
of literally nothing that's

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:28.960
right at the frontier,
it's pretty amazing.

00:11:28.960 --> 00:11:30.540
So what's behind this?

00:11:30.540 --> 00:11:34.380
So in the 1960s
period, Linsu Kim

00:11:34.380 --> 00:11:37.230
argues that Korean
firms are on a-- what he

00:11:37.230 --> 00:11:39.540
calls a leadership trajectory.

00:11:39.540 --> 00:11:45.090
And the government is on a model
of what he calls forced march

00:11:45.090 --> 00:11:46.170
industrialization.

00:11:46.170 --> 00:11:48.690
The government is supplying
education through college.

00:11:48.690 --> 00:11:50.250
On the demand
side, it's creating

00:11:50.250 --> 00:11:53.140
chebols, which are somewhat
akin to the keiretsu model we

00:11:53.140 --> 00:11:54.916
were talking about in Japan.

00:11:54.916 --> 00:11:58.930
In other words, these are
major industry leaders.

00:11:58.930 --> 00:12:05.040
And the difficulty in this mix,
in the government of the time,

00:12:05.040 --> 00:12:07.380
was its corruption.

00:12:07.380 --> 00:12:10.160
And this is--

00:12:10.160 --> 00:12:14.180
Korea's is still in the hands of
a dictatorship with corruption

00:12:14.180 --> 00:12:15.230
problems.

00:12:15.230 --> 00:12:16.670
And problem with
corruption is it

00:12:16.670 --> 00:12:19.310
creates tremendous
uncertainty in your business.

00:12:24.420 --> 00:12:28.340
That was kind of a
difficult factor,

00:12:28.340 --> 00:12:30.680
but nonetheless, the government
was playing a key role

00:12:30.680 --> 00:12:35.130
in pushing these major
companies on a march

00:12:35.130 --> 00:12:37.670
to a strong international role.

00:12:37.670 --> 00:12:39.170
AUDIENCE: Could you
clarify what you

00:12:39.170 --> 00:12:42.050
mean by corruption creates
tremendous business

00:12:42.050 --> 00:12:43.503
uncertainty?

00:12:43.503 --> 00:12:45.170
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN:
You're not competing

00:12:45.170 --> 00:12:49.190
with other firms based
upon your superior products

00:12:49.190 --> 00:12:52.430
and your superior
ability to manufacture.

00:12:52.430 --> 00:12:55.610
Suddenly, a wild card
is thrown into the mix

00:12:55.610 --> 00:12:58.870
and you've got to cope
with the government,

00:12:58.870 --> 00:13:01.910
and buying off the government,
and buying government support,

00:13:01.910 --> 00:13:03.560
if you want to stay ahead.

00:13:03.560 --> 00:13:07.060
So it creates a whole new
variable that's much less--

00:13:07.060 --> 00:13:11.090
that can't be managed by your
business processes and systems.

00:13:13.610 --> 00:13:20.360
So that's why when we read
the World Economic Report,

00:13:20.360 --> 00:13:21.980
that's why corruption
was actually

00:13:21.980 --> 00:13:24.710
one of the factors
that was considered

00:13:24.710 --> 00:13:26.870
in the strength of your
economy because it can

00:13:26.870 --> 00:13:30.620
be so disruptive of the ability
to have a reasonable and fair

00:13:30.620 --> 00:13:32.240
competition system.

00:13:32.240 --> 00:13:36.080
So the chebols, to go back to
our discussion-- that chebols

00:13:36.080 --> 00:13:39.170
were key to building
and capturing

00:13:39.170 --> 00:13:41.300
these large-scale industries.

00:13:41.300 --> 00:13:46.130
Now, Korea, when creates
these major companies that

00:13:46.130 --> 00:13:49.550
dominate industrial
sectors, they

00:13:49.550 --> 00:13:54.080
tend to block entry by small
and medium-sized enterprises.

00:13:54.080 --> 00:13:55.880
So Korea, at the
same time, is not

00:13:55.880 --> 00:14:00.980
creating a system of strong,
small, and midsized firms.

00:14:00.980 --> 00:14:04.790
It's really focused on
creating these big chebols that

00:14:04.790 --> 00:14:08.930
can really function in
international marketplaces.

00:14:08.930 --> 00:14:10.970
But that, in turn, can
create inefficiencies,

00:14:10.970 --> 00:14:14.330
as well, Kim argues.

00:14:14.330 --> 00:14:17.465
In education, Korea hit on a
model of widespread education,

00:14:17.465 --> 00:14:20.360
and that has been--
it's a dramatic story.

00:14:20.360 --> 00:14:24.050
The college completion
rate there is breathtaking.

00:14:24.050 --> 00:14:30.240
And the focus is to get a very
highly educated population,

00:14:30.240 --> 00:14:31.830
which they have achieved.

00:14:31.830 --> 00:14:33.930
And then that highly
educated population

00:14:33.930 --> 00:14:37.810
is able to staff ever more
sophisticated industries.

00:14:37.810 --> 00:14:38.970
That's the model.

00:14:41.700 --> 00:14:42.450
And it works.

00:14:42.450 --> 00:14:46.470
The one thing they don't
do is move their colleges

00:14:46.470 --> 00:14:49.980
into research universities,
which Kim argues is still

00:14:49.980 --> 00:14:52.830
a part of the model that
needs to be achieved.

00:14:52.830 --> 00:14:56.040
There's a very strong
export strategy in Korea.

00:14:59.622 --> 00:15:00.330
Martin, go ahead.

00:15:00.330 --> 00:15:01.460
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] the
research institutions,

00:15:01.460 --> 00:15:03.270
do they just send
their people to study

00:15:03.270 --> 00:15:04.690
at research institutions then?

00:15:04.690 --> 00:15:06.060
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: Yeah,
they have governmentally

00:15:06.060 --> 00:15:09.030
supported research institutions,
and I'll get to a little more

00:15:09.030 --> 00:15:11.790
on that in a second.

00:15:11.790 --> 00:15:15.780
The wisdom of the US model is
that you combine the education

00:15:15.780 --> 00:15:18.585
system with the research system.

00:15:18.585 --> 00:15:20.460
And therefore, you create
a tremendous amount

00:15:20.460 --> 00:15:22.650
of learning by doing.

00:15:22.650 --> 00:15:24.480
It seems to work pretty well.

00:15:24.480 --> 00:15:26.640
If you're just supporting
research institutions

00:15:26.640 --> 00:15:28.740
as separate research
entities, you

00:15:28.740 --> 00:15:35.370
miss the dynamics of that
education connection tie.

00:15:35.370 --> 00:15:36.900
Doesn't work as smoothly.

00:15:36.900 --> 00:15:38.775
AUDIENCE: I ask because
I think it might just

00:15:38.775 --> 00:15:41.317
be a way for them to cut costs,
because research institutions

00:15:41.317 --> 00:15:42.300
might be more complex.

00:15:42.300 --> 00:15:44.633
So they focus on making a
really good college education,

00:15:44.633 --> 00:15:47.700
then exporting people to do
research in other countries,

00:15:47.700 --> 00:15:48.408
then they might--

00:15:48.408 --> 00:15:50.742
it just might be something
to make it more efficient for

00:15:50.742 --> 00:15:51.275
[INAUDIBLE].

00:15:51.275 --> 00:15:52.900
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN:
Yeah, I think there

00:15:52.900 --> 00:15:57.060
are certainly arguments
there, Martin.

00:15:57.060 --> 00:15:59.340
One thing that the
Korean government did do

00:15:59.340 --> 00:16:03.360
was it forced its big companies
into international competition.

00:16:03.360 --> 00:16:05.880
So they've got a fairly
mercantilist model

00:16:05.880 --> 00:16:07.560
of not allowing--

00:16:07.560 --> 00:16:10.840
of protecting a domestic
market their companies.

00:16:10.840 --> 00:16:13.080
But it's not that big
a domestic market.

00:16:13.080 --> 00:16:14.940
They've got to force
their companies out

00:16:14.940 --> 00:16:17.430
into international
competition, and they do it.

00:16:20.010 --> 00:16:22.140
And that builds tremendous
competitive strength

00:16:22.140 --> 00:16:23.112
in these firms.

00:16:23.112 --> 00:16:25.070
We look around and see
the strong Korean firms.

00:16:25.070 --> 00:16:27.900
It's a pretty remarkable story.

00:16:27.900 --> 00:16:30.090
In terms of tech
transfer policy,

00:16:30.090 --> 00:16:34.680
the policy was initially
largely a reverse engineering

00:16:34.680 --> 00:16:38.010
of technologies
brought in from abroad.

00:16:38.010 --> 00:16:40.650
But critical
capabilities are being

00:16:40.650 --> 00:16:44.130
developed as part of this
reverse engineering effort.

00:16:44.130 --> 00:16:48.690
R&D policy-- it's focused,
as I mentioned before,

00:16:48.690 --> 00:16:50.700
on these government
research institutions.

00:16:53.960 --> 00:16:57.270
The GRIs provide more of a--

00:16:57.270 --> 00:17:00.570
rather than influencing
industry R&D as much,

00:17:00.570 --> 00:17:04.140
it's more of a talent
base and support base--

00:17:04.140 --> 00:17:07.010
as you were, indeed,
suggesting, Martine--

00:17:07.010 --> 00:17:09.329
for companies.

00:17:09.329 --> 00:17:12.960
Kim also has this very
interesting discussion

00:17:12.960 --> 00:17:16.740
of Korean culture
here and what's

00:17:16.740 --> 00:17:21.599
going on that
matches the evolution

00:17:21.599 --> 00:17:24.450
of this remarkable
economic growth.

00:17:24.450 --> 00:17:29.010
So he argues that in Korea,
this interesting blend

00:17:29.010 --> 00:17:33.975
of an Asian Confucian
culture of family

00:17:33.975 --> 00:17:40.020
and collective support and
a collective orientation

00:17:40.020 --> 00:17:42.660
gets merged with a pretty high
level of-- quite high level

00:17:42.660 --> 00:17:45.960
of Christianity and its
individualism for a very

00:17:45.960 --> 00:17:47.480
interesting combination.

00:17:47.480 --> 00:17:49.590
It affects strengths on
both ends-- strengths

00:17:49.590 --> 00:17:52.380
on the collectivity side,
but also the strengths

00:17:52.380 --> 00:17:55.710
on the individuals side.

00:17:55.710 --> 00:17:58.770
Some of you may have
thoughts about that.

00:17:58.770 --> 00:18:01.050
Also the Korean War
itself, as we discussed,

00:18:01.050 --> 00:18:09.510
left the country destroyed,
and ended village culture,

00:18:09.510 --> 00:18:15.900
but amalgamated the
population in a way that

00:18:15.900 --> 00:18:18.030
created a certain
kind of flexibility,

00:18:18.030 --> 00:18:23.280
as the old social and cultural
barriers were swept away.

00:18:23.280 --> 00:18:25.970
So that it wasn't
all bad, I guess

00:18:25.970 --> 00:18:29.850
would be Kim's conclusion.

00:18:29.850 --> 00:18:32.880
And then because
it's a country that

00:18:32.880 --> 00:18:37.230
has constant threat of
war with North Korea,

00:18:37.230 --> 00:18:42.480
the universal military service
provides a huge training

00:18:42.480 --> 00:18:48.450
opportunity for a
management class, in effect.

00:18:48.450 --> 00:18:50.760
And since militaries,
to be effective,

00:18:50.760 --> 00:18:54.790
has to be pretty meritocratic.

00:18:54.790 --> 00:18:57.540
It introduces a whole
meritocracy system

00:18:57.540 --> 00:19:02.460
into Korean society
and culture, replacing

00:19:02.460 --> 00:19:05.940
an older village, more
class-oriented kind of culture.

00:19:10.200 --> 00:19:11.700
There's a series
of forces here that

00:19:11.700 --> 00:19:14.010
tend to create a certain
amount of social mobility

00:19:14.010 --> 00:19:18.060
and elimination of historic
social classes going on here,

00:19:18.060 --> 00:19:23.320
which is part of the
story that enables,

00:19:23.320 --> 00:19:26.100
Kim argues, Korea to thrive.

00:19:28.700 --> 00:19:32.270
That military service is
an interesting feature.

00:19:32.270 --> 00:19:35.180
Our military, back in the days--

00:19:35.180 --> 00:19:38.630
which I can remember and you
can't-- when there was a draft,

00:19:38.630 --> 00:19:42.860
the US military was actually a
very important integrated force

00:19:42.860 --> 00:19:44.810
in this society.

00:19:44.810 --> 00:19:49.400
That was a very
critical step in the US

00:19:49.400 --> 00:19:50.990
to promote racial
integration, when

00:19:50.990 --> 00:19:57.150
you had integrated military
units at the height of threats

00:19:57.150 --> 00:19:59.340
of warfare and combat.

00:19:59.340 --> 00:20:02.170
It really changed a lot
of thinking in society.

00:20:02.170 --> 00:20:04.620
So there's just an
interesting side note

00:20:04.620 --> 00:20:09.600
there about what that kind
of social organization

00:20:09.600 --> 00:20:12.130
can mean in a social context.

00:20:12.130 --> 00:20:15.150
But Kim argues that
it's important in Korea.

00:20:15.150 --> 00:20:20.730
So Korea develops, he argues,
a learning technology culture.

00:20:20.730 --> 00:20:24.690
So the firms go from what
he calls poaching and kind

00:20:24.690 --> 00:20:28.200
of reverse engineering, and
then to reverse engineering,

00:20:28.200 --> 00:20:32.220
then to R&D, and then
to true innovation.

00:20:32.220 --> 00:20:34.530
So Korea's certainly right
at the technology frontier

00:20:34.530 --> 00:20:36.060
in a whole series of areas.

00:20:36.060 --> 00:20:39.180
And they've moved through a
series of steps to get there.

00:20:39.180 --> 00:20:43.890
And Kim argues that
these are steps.

00:20:43.890 --> 00:20:46.140
And you tend to
frown on poaching

00:20:46.140 --> 00:20:51.690
and reverse engineering,
but let me remind us

00:20:51.690 --> 00:20:59.480
that the first textile
industry in the US

00:20:59.480 --> 00:21:02.330
was set up in
Pawtucket, Rhode Island

00:21:02.330 --> 00:21:06.200
by an English immigrant
named Samuel Slater.

00:21:06.200 --> 00:21:13.280
And Samuel Slater is working in
the British textile factories.

00:21:13.280 --> 00:21:14.990
And the British
textile factories

00:21:14.990 --> 00:21:17.720
realized they've got a
monopoly on textile production

00:21:17.720 --> 00:21:19.490
efficiency worldwide,
and they don't

00:21:19.490 --> 00:21:21.320
want anybody else to have it.

00:21:21.320 --> 00:21:23.330
So you're subjected
to a body search

00:21:23.330 --> 00:21:26.030
to make sure you're not walking
out with plans, if you're

00:21:26.030 --> 00:21:28.020
an employee in these factories.

00:21:28.020 --> 00:21:31.280
And Slater's searched every
time he leaves the factory.

00:21:31.280 --> 00:21:33.110
What his British
employers didn't realize

00:21:33.110 --> 00:21:37.010
is that he had a
photographic memory.

00:21:37.010 --> 00:21:39.770
So he worked with his
textile equipment,

00:21:39.770 --> 00:21:41.770
goes to the United
States, sets up

00:21:41.770 --> 00:21:43.520
the same stuff in
Pawtucket, Rhode Island,

00:21:43.520 --> 00:21:46.700
and brings a textile industry.

00:21:46.700 --> 00:21:49.927
So talk about poaching--
that's straight poaching.

00:21:49.927 --> 00:21:51.760
So the textile industry
in the United States

00:21:51.760 --> 00:21:54.730
is organized essentially
through the same model,

00:21:54.730 --> 00:21:57.095
and arguably, the same
stages we went through.

00:21:57.095 --> 00:21:58.970
When Lawrence and Lowell
are established here

00:21:58.970 --> 00:22:01.330
in Massachusetts,
we're definitely

00:22:01.330 --> 00:22:04.090
into technological
advances at the frontier

00:22:04.090 --> 00:22:06.370
of textile production
at the time.

00:22:06.370 --> 00:22:10.990
So in a way, we went
through similar stages.

00:22:10.990 --> 00:22:15.460
R&D investment-- so there's
very heavy R&D in the industry

00:22:15.460 --> 00:22:19.990
chebols, but the issue Kim
raises is that there's not

00:22:19.990 --> 00:22:20.860
enough SMEs--

00:22:20.860 --> 00:22:24.570
small and midsize enterprises--
to provide out-of-the-box ideas

00:22:24.570 --> 00:22:28.340
in thinking in the mix, and that
that's a problem in the system.

00:22:28.340 --> 00:22:31.620
And he argues that
needs to be changed.

00:22:31.620 --> 00:22:35.100
But Korea, overall, has got a
very high R&D to GDP ratio--

00:22:35.100 --> 00:22:36.990
higher than the US.

00:22:36.990 --> 00:22:41.580
So the problems are
limited university R&D,

00:22:41.580 --> 00:22:44.325
the need for a larger
SME entrepreneurial base.

00:22:47.040 --> 00:22:49.350
He argues that a more
liberalized economy

00:22:49.350 --> 00:22:55.920
away from the kind of
elite chebol control

00:22:55.920 --> 00:22:57.900
is an important step.

00:22:57.900 --> 00:23:00.990
But there's a lot of
lessons here from Korea--

00:23:00.990 --> 00:23:04.260
the role of a strong
governmental leadership

00:23:04.260 --> 00:23:07.650
in creating strong
firms, but in effect,

00:23:07.650 --> 00:23:13.620
forcing them into
international competition.

00:23:13.620 --> 00:23:15.870
It's Darwinian.

00:23:15.870 --> 00:23:19.560
And the government
education programs

00:23:19.560 --> 00:23:24.810
that facilitate very, very
strong talent base country

00:23:24.810 --> 00:23:26.230
are clearly key.

00:23:26.230 --> 00:23:32.660
And the government use
crisis to force its firms--

00:23:32.660 --> 00:23:35.660
it would, in effect, force
its firms into a crisis

00:23:35.660 --> 00:23:37.940
kind of circumstance, so
that they would really learn

00:23:37.940 --> 00:23:39.740
how to compete and survive.

00:23:39.740 --> 00:23:43.590
So those are all interesting
lessons from Korea.

00:23:43.590 --> 00:23:47.865
So who's got Linsu Kim,
and who's got Glenn Fong?

00:23:47.865 --> 00:23:49.200
AUDIENCE: I have the Kim.

00:23:49.200 --> 00:23:51.320
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: OK,
and you've got Glenn Fong.

00:23:51.320 --> 00:23:53.186
So why don't we start
with you, Matthew?

00:23:53.186 --> 00:23:54.570
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:23:54.570 --> 00:23:57.530
So I think besides
[INAUDIBLE] covering

00:23:57.530 --> 00:24:04.100
a lot of his main points I think
really interesting is Glenn

00:24:04.100 --> 00:24:07.340
Fong, he turns this
argument on its head--

00:24:07.340 --> 00:24:11.210
where most people think
about political structures

00:24:11.210 --> 00:24:14.330
determining how
competitive an economy is.

00:24:14.330 --> 00:24:16.580
But he looks at
the competitiveness

00:24:16.580 --> 00:24:19.460
of the economy, internationally
competitive-- competitiveness

00:24:19.460 --> 00:24:25.280
driving the imperative of
the political structure,

00:24:25.280 --> 00:24:28.530
and how involved it becomes
as the country moves

00:24:28.530 --> 00:24:34.020
from pursuer after the pioneer
to a follower at the frontier.

00:24:34.020 --> 00:24:35.950
And he gives the
example of Japan.

00:24:35.950 --> 00:24:38.960
One theme that I saw
throughout the question

00:24:38.960 --> 00:24:43.720
is how much of that process
is a conscious decision,

00:24:43.720 --> 00:24:47.570
or how much of it kind
of happens naturally?

00:24:47.570 --> 00:24:51.080
Is there a certain point when
the government says, hey, we

00:24:51.080 --> 00:24:55.160
are approaching your frontier
now, we should be hands-off?

00:24:55.160 --> 00:24:57.740
How does that end up
happening in practice?

00:25:05.670 --> 00:25:07.830
AUDIENCE: I think the
approach is probably

00:25:07.830 --> 00:25:11.350
the most difficult
part of the process,

00:25:11.350 --> 00:25:17.850
just because you have
to set up and protect--

00:25:17.850 --> 00:25:20.460
the chebols and
systems have to be

00:25:20.460 --> 00:25:24.980
put in place that borrowed on
these sort of cultural values.

00:25:24.980 --> 00:25:28.410
You mentioned the strong
military service at this point.

00:25:28.410 --> 00:25:31.510
And a lot of other things
have to come together.

00:25:31.510 --> 00:25:36.270
And so I would peg the approach
as sort of the hardest part.

00:25:36.270 --> 00:25:39.600
But I think once you
have your system set up

00:25:39.600 --> 00:25:43.830
and you're looking to
compete internationally,

00:25:43.830 --> 00:25:48.120
I think that's the point
where you have to let go.

00:25:48.120 --> 00:25:51.980
But I think you need to
reach some sort of maturity.

00:25:51.980 --> 00:25:53.800
And I think it's
pretty easy to say, OK,

00:25:53.800 --> 00:25:56.460
we've copied everything that
we've been able to copy.

00:25:56.460 --> 00:25:57.370
What's next?

00:25:57.370 --> 00:25:58.920
And if you don't
have anything next,

00:25:58.920 --> 00:26:04.920
it might be tough to
diversify and let things go.

00:26:04.920 --> 00:26:07.225
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: So
Rasheed just to used

00:26:07.225 --> 00:26:10.272
Glenn Fong's terms-- and correct
me if I've got this, Matthew--

00:26:10.272 --> 00:26:18.320
but when you move from pursuer
of the pioneer to right

00:26:18.320 --> 00:26:20.582
at the technological
frontier, that's

00:26:20.582 --> 00:26:22.040
the moment where
you ought to think

00:26:22.040 --> 00:26:23.990
about your organizational model.

00:26:23.990 --> 00:26:26.450
Because to get to that
world-class leadership

00:26:26.450 --> 00:26:29.240
on a continuing
basis may require

00:26:29.240 --> 00:26:33.800
you to decentralize and
change your government role,

00:26:33.800 --> 00:26:36.050
to build a more
collaborative model

00:26:36.050 --> 00:26:37.810
and rely on a large
number of players

00:26:37.810 --> 00:26:40.770
to be able to contribute ideas.

00:26:40.770 --> 00:26:42.160
Would you agree, Matt?

00:26:42.160 --> 00:26:42.930
Is that right?

00:26:42.930 --> 00:26:44.310
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:26:44.310 --> 00:26:46.590
Well, the way that
you said it almost

00:26:46.590 --> 00:26:48.750
implies that there's
a conscious decision

00:26:48.750 --> 00:26:51.985
about how much the government's
going to be involved.

00:26:51.985 --> 00:26:53.610
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN:
I think, for Japan,

00:26:53.610 --> 00:26:58.410
what happened was they realized
they missed the IT revolution

00:26:58.410 --> 00:27:03.470
that was led by US companies.

00:27:03.470 --> 00:27:06.180
And we'll read about DARPA
and the IT revolution

00:27:06.180 --> 00:27:09.340
in a later class, but you'll
see where that comes from.

00:27:09.340 --> 00:27:11.800
And by having an R&D
system that was pretty

00:27:11.800 --> 00:27:14.560
focused on applied
work with industry,

00:27:14.560 --> 00:27:18.250
as opposed to
university research,

00:27:18.250 --> 00:27:22.030
you get very good at the
incremental advances,

00:27:22.030 --> 00:27:25.550
but you may miss
fundamental breakthroughs.

00:27:25.550 --> 00:27:29.850
And so I think Japan
is waking up, in 1998,

00:27:29.850 --> 00:27:32.610
to these realities, and trying
to think about its innovation

00:27:32.610 --> 00:27:37.470
organization to open up larger
menu of innovation practices.

00:27:37.470 --> 00:27:39.680
That would be my guess.

00:27:39.680 --> 00:27:42.480
But I think that's right.

00:27:42.480 --> 00:27:45.290
AUDIENCE: And the
other thing I had was--

00:27:45.290 --> 00:27:47.460
use this, Japan as an example--

00:27:47.460 --> 00:27:51.460
looking at Korea, it does
seem to fit the model.

00:27:51.460 --> 00:27:56.130
But to what extent does this
model actually generalize?

00:27:56.130 --> 00:28:00.263
Off the the top of my head, I
think of the US space program

00:28:00.263 --> 00:28:01.930
or something like the
Manhattan Project,

00:28:01.930 --> 00:28:06.210
where it's very much at
the competitive frontier,

00:28:06.210 --> 00:28:10.530
but strong government
involvement and basically

00:28:10.530 --> 00:28:16.040
targeting technologies
did lead to major advances

00:28:16.040 --> 00:28:18.968
in research and development.

00:28:26.570 --> 00:28:28.350
Do we think that it--

00:28:28.350 --> 00:28:30.170
that the model actually
works all the time?

00:28:30.170 --> 00:28:33.050
Or is it necessarily even
the best thing to be doing?

00:28:49.914 --> 00:28:51.706
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN:
Help out Matthew, team.

00:28:51.706 --> 00:28:53.240
Give him a hand here.

00:28:53.240 --> 00:28:54.950
He's got a lifeline out there.

00:28:54.950 --> 00:28:56.492
AUDIENCE: Well, I'm
curious as to why

00:28:56.492 --> 00:28:58.670
we, in the general
discourse of innovation,

00:28:58.670 --> 00:29:00.610
only pay attention take
East Asian countries,

00:29:00.610 --> 00:29:03.380
or largely pay attention
to East Asian countries.

00:29:03.380 --> 00:29:06.500
Because you never hear about
United States and innovations

00:29:06.500 --> 00:29:08.810
here being juxtaposed
to, say, innovations

00:29:08.810 --> 00:29:14.000
in central or South America,
or even Eastern Europe.

00:29:14.000 --> 00:29:16.640
And perhaps
technological advances

00:29:16.640 --> 00:29:23.870
are not as impressive there,
or the breadth of their impact

00:29:23.870 --> 00:29:25.760
is not as extensive.

00:29:25.760 --> 00:29:27.680
And at the same
time, I think there

00:29:27.680 --> 00:29:29.600
has to be innovation
occurring in other parts

00:29:29.600 --> 00:29:32.640
of the world that are not
South Korea, Germany, China,

00:29:32.640 --> 00:29:33.860
and Japan.

00:29:33.860 --> 00:29:37.280
So to what extent is that
premised on that kind

00:29:37.280 --> 00:29:39.710
of American paranoia that was
highlighted in the Hughes'

00:29:39.710 --> 00:29:41.240
piece against East Asia?

00:29:43.800 --> 00:29:45.420
AUDIENCE: I think
a good follow-up

00:29:45.420 --> 00:29:49.492
is we don't have a good--
