innovation cycles or products

00:30:51.440 --> 00:30:52.482
that we could learn from?

00:30:56.840 --> 00:30:59.410
AUDIENCE: Just to add onto
that-- so I think the reason we

00:30:59.410 --> 00:31:03.190
look into Asia a lot is
because they were economies

00:31:03.190 --> 00:31:07.900
that weren't doing great, and
then they pretty much did a 180

00:31:07.900 --> 00:31:09.418
in less 30 years.

00:31:09.418 --> 00:31:10.960
And there are a lot
of factors to it.

00:31:10.960 --> 00:31:13.500
A lot of it was having very
strong leaders coming from

00:31:13.500 --> 00:31:16.960
periods of not doing too well--
so they were more unified--

00:31:16.960 --> 00:31:20.063
and then having a
strong young population.

00:31:20.063 --> 00:31:21.730
So most of the countries
that did really

00:31:21.730 --> 00:31:25.300
well during this period or
had a age pyramid like this.

00:31:25.300 --> 00:31:28.210
So it's a lot of young
people, very few old people.

00:31:28.210 --> 00:31:31.610
And they were able to move
very quickly, and especially

00:31:31.610 --> 00:31:34.060
because they have
these strong leaders.

00:31:34.060 --> 00:31:36.820
These other countries, I
think a lot in Latin America,

00:31:36.820 --> 00:31:39.652
they don't have these strong
leaders or these periods that

00:31:39.652 --> 00:31:41.110
come up beforehand,
so there hasn't

00:31:41.110 --> 00:31:43.860
been rapid growth,
innovations-- even though there

00:31:43.860 --> 00:31:46.235
has been a lot of innovation,
especially in manufacturing

00:31:46.235 --> 00:31:48.438
in Brazil, parts of Mexico.

00:31:48.438 --> 00:31:50.980
So I think it's just we haven't
paid too much attention to it

00:31:50.980 --> 00:31:52.660
because it doesn't
seem like a threat.

00:31:52.660 --> 00:31:53.950
But these other
countries have moved

00:31:53.950 --> 00:31:55.375
so quickly that
it does seem-- you

00:31:55.375 --> 00:31:56.625
can see it more than a threat.

00:31:56.625 --> 00:31:58.100
Because if you
look at Singapore,

00:31:58.100 --> 00:32:00.100
it was a country that was
pretty much not there.

00:32:00.100 --> 00:32:02.080
They had a very
strong leader, was

00:32:02.080 --> 00:32:05.200
able to make quick decisions
that are very strong,

00:32:05.200 --> 00:32:06.670
and be very strong
in saying, this

00:32:06.670 --> 00:32:08.878
is what I believe, this is
what I think we should do,

00:32:08.878 --> 00:32:10.980
and then going after it.

00:32:10.980 --> 00:32:14.170
And they were able to
completely 180 their economy.

00:32:14.170 --> 00:32:17.710
And I think we're also talking
about the role of government

00:32:17.710 --> 00:32:21.100
in the US has committees making
decisions for innovation.

00:32:21.100 --> 00:32:23.840
But actually, Charlie
Munger, who-- everyone

00:32:23.840 --> 00:32:25.630
knows Warren Buffett, right?

00:32:25.630 --> 00:32:26.195
More or less?

00:32:26.195 --> 00:32:27.820
Charlie Munger's his
right-hand person.

00:32:27.820 --> 00:32:31.240
And he says, in the
past, in general,

00:32:31.240 --> 00:32:34.450
countries do better when its
one very smart, talented leader,

00:32:34.450 --> 00:32:36.330
because they can make
these hard decisions.

00:32:36.330 --> 00:32:38.420
And in the US, we do
have an executive,

00:32:38.420 --> 00:32:40.120
but I think everybody
at this table

00:32:40.120 --> 00:32:41.860
can agree that people
don't really say,

00:32:41.860 --> 00:32:44.870
he said that-- we should do it.

00:32:44.870 --> 00:32:48.340
So the benefit is these
are very credible leaders

00:32:48.340 --> 00:32:50.050
that most of the
time, when they make

00:32:50.050 --> 00:32:52.510
it that position from
a downturn period,

00:32:52.510 --> 00:32:54.550
are very talented and skilled.

00:32:54.550 --> 00:32:55.580
And they do make bets.

00:32:55.580 --> 00:32:57.080
They can make these
[INAUDIBLE] say,

00:32:57.080 --> 00:32:58.420
you know what, this
is an industry that's

00:32:58.420 --> 00:32:59.590
going to grow very quickly.

00:32:59.590 --> 00:33:00.760
Let's put three people.

00:33:00.760 --> 00:33:03.480
There's like 3, 30, 40
companies that could do well,

00:33:03.480 --> 00:33:05.480
but I think these three
are really going to win,

00:33:05.480 --> 00:33:07.080
and we're going to put all
our eggs in this basket,

00:33:07.080 --> 00:33:08.170
and we're going to do well.

00:33:08.170 --> 00:33:09.920
And that's something
that's very, I guess,

00:33:09.920 --> 00:33:12.220
I would call un-American,
because we're very much--

00:33:12.220 --> 00:33:13.450
everybody can go about it.

00:33:13.450 --> 00:33:15.600
We want to leave opportunity.

00:33:15.600 --> 00:33:17.458
But these countries do
have this capability,

00:33:17.458 --> 00:33:19.000
and they have already
shown that they

00:33:19.000 --> 00:33:22.220
can grow so quickly, versus
as other countries, I think--

00:33:22.220 --> 00:33:25.090
I think another thing too is
Latin America, Russia, we still

00:33:25.090 --> 00:33:26.620
see a lot of corruption.

00:33:26.620 --> 00:33:28.690
These other countries were
able to get rid of it.

00:33:28.690 --> 00:33:31.703
Like Singapore, what Lee
Kuan Yew did was say,

00:33:31.703 --> 00:33:33.620
I'm going to pay everyone
about twice as much,

00:33:33.620 --> 00:33:35.680
but if I find out that
you're being corrupt,

00:33:35.680 --> 00:33:37.820
you guys are pretty much done.

00:33:37.820 --> 00:33:39.760
So I don't know if it
was a death penalty

00:33:39.760 --> 00:33:41.830
or it was very severe
sanctions, but it was also

00:33:41.830 --> 00:33:43.898
severe sanctions upon
them and their families.

00:33:43.898 --> 00:33:46.190
So that's a completely
different way of going about it.

00:33:46.190 --> 00:33:48.440
So I think just don't see
other countries as a threat,

00:33:48.440 --> 00:33:51.280
even though they have
good capabilities.

00:33:51.280 --> 00:33:55.120
But these countries did do
amazing things in 30, 20 years

00:33:55.120 --> 00:33:57.015
that can't be taken lightly.

00:33:57.015 --> 00:33:58.390
But you could also
debate that it

00:33:58.390 --> 00:34:00.807
was because there was very
young populations, because also

00:34:00.807 --> 00:34:06.308
Japan and South Korea had
stagnation right after.

00:34:06.308 --> 00:34:06.850
Final point--

00:34:06.850 --> 00:34:10.860
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: So, Martin,
that's a very political economy

00:34:10.860 --> 00:34:14.020
perspective.

00:34:14.020 --> 00:34:19.500
Going back to some of the points
that Matt was making earlier,

00:34:19.500 --> 00:34:22.290
I think the central
Glenn Fong argument

00:34:22.290 --> 00:34:25.920
is that that may get you a fair
distance for a period of time,

00:34:25.920 --> 00:34:27.780
as you're getting
to the frontier.

00:34:27.780 --> 00:34:29.550
But then when you
get to the frontier,

00:34:29.550 --> 00:34:32.850
you better figure
out a more bottom-up,

00:34:32.850 --> 00:34:36.980
more collaborative kind of model
if you want to keep the ideas--

00:34:36.980 --> 00:34:40.110
if you need that
big mix of ideas

00:34:40.110 --> 00:34:43.409
that's going to enable you to go
to a series of the next things.

00:34:43.409 --> 00:34:45.480
That's Fong's argument.

00:34:45.480 --> 00:34:48.960
And his point is
that Japan really

00:34:48.960 --> 00:34:51.858
had to reorganize
its innovations away

00:34:51.858 --> 00:34:53.650
from the political
economy kind of approach

00:34:53.650 --> 00:34:56.159
you were describing
before to really a very

00:34:56.159 --> 00:34:59.220
different organization,
when it reached

00:34:59.220 --> 00:35:02.883
that moment of [INAUDIBLE]
innovation and competition.

00:35:06.498 --> 00:35:10.482
[INAUDIBLE],, in response
to your question, in a way,

00:35:10.482 --> 00:35:12.190
I want to go back to
what we talked about

00:35:12.190 --> 00:35:15.970
in the first class.

00:35:15.970 --> 00:35:19.570
For a long time, we thought
that this innovation system

00:35:19.570 --> 00:35:24.440
stuff was the way in which
the rich countries got rich.

00:35:24.440 --> 00:35:27.620
It was just a way to
build further wealth

00:35:27.620 --> 00:35:30.200
in a relatively modest
number of countries

00:35:30.200 --> 00:35:33.170
that figured out how to dominate
and lead these innovation

00:35:33.170 --> 00:35:34.550
systems.

00:35:34.550 --> 00:35:39.350
But then other things
started happening.

00:35:39.350 --> 00:35:44.120
Korea comes up from
being totally destroyed.

00:35:44.120 --> 00:35:45.610
Taiwan's somewhat similar.

00:35:48.230 --> 00:35:50.360
Economies like India,
which is obviously

00:35:50.360 --> 00:35:52.880
one of the poorest
in the world, is

00:35:52.880 --> 00:35:56.930
able to start building a very
significant middle class.

00:35:56.930 --> 00:35:59.850
And China's the latest
element in this story.

00:35:59.850 --> 00:36:02.540
In other words, an
innovation-based growth model

00:36:02.540 --> 00:36:09.390
can be pervasive and work
in the developing world.

00:36:09.390 --> 00:36:11.300
Now, we've managed
to translate that

00:36:11.300 --> 00:36:15.920
at pretty interesting
scale in parts of Asia.

00:36:15.920 --> 00:36:18.260
You're exactly right--
we haven't translated,

00:36:18.260 --> 00:36:19.850
with the possible
exception of Brazil,

00:36:19.850 --> 00:36:22.126
into a pervasive model in
Latin America, for example.

00:36:25.700 --> 00:36:28.010
One of the options for
doing a paper in this course

00:36:28.010 --> 00:36:31.790
is to look at other national
innovation systems and dive

00:36:31.790 --> 00:36:32.690
into them.

00:36:32.690 --> 00:36:34.670
And I really hope of
you will pursue this.

00:36:40.980 --> 00:36:43.930
We don't particularly focus
on this in this class,

00:36:43.930 --> 00:36:45.120
although we could.

00:36:45.120 --> 00:36:48.330
But the Brazil story's
absolutely fascinating,

00:36:48.330 --> 00:36:50.098
and a remarkable story.

00:36:50.098 --> 00:36:52.390
Obviously, they're in a fair
amount of economic trouble

00:36:52.390 --> 00:36:55.320
from macro factors
at the moment.

00:36:55.320 --> 00:36:59.155
But nonetheless, it's a very
promising and encouraging story

00:36:59.155 --> 00:37:01.080
overall.

00:37:01.080 --> 00:37:03.580
But there are others, and there
are other parts of the world

00:37:03.580 --> 00:37:04.870
too.

