00:47:35.490 --> 00:47:37.320
recovered from
the 2001 recession

00:47:37.320 --> 00:47:42.510
by the time the 2007, 2008,
2009 recession is on us.

00:47:42.510 --> 00:47:48.330
So there may be an argument
that something fundamental

00:47:48.330 --> 00:47:50.510
is going on structurally
in the economy,

00:47:50.510 --> 00:47:52.440
when you see a chart like that.

00:47:52.440 --> 00:47:56.130
In each successive recession,
it's less of a business cycle.

00:47:56.130 --> 00:47:58.710
It's more structural.

00:47:58.710 --> 00:48:03.960
And it looks like there
are deep structural causes

00:48:03.960 --> 00:48:07.530
in these manufacturing
employment declines, when you

00:48:07.530 --> 00:48:09.240
start seeing a chart like this.

00:48:09.240 --> 00:48:11.640
We'll talk more
about it next week,

00:48:11.640 --> 00:48:13.560
but here's declining
median income

00:48:13.560 --> 00:48:16.920
for the US, which we'll talk
more about next week too.

00:48:16.920 --> 00:48:21.120
So particularly pay
attention to men, who were--

00:48:21.120 --> 00:48:24.600
tend to historically have played
a larger role in manufacturing

00:48:24.600 --> 00:48:27.780
industries in the US.

00:48:27.780 --> 00:48:33.210
So this is change in median
real earnings for men and women

00:48:33.210 --> 00:48:35.850
from 1990 to 2013--

00:48:35.850 --> 00:48:42.040
so an extended period
from '90 to '13.

00:48:42.040 --> 00:48:44.890
No high school diploma, men--

00:48:44.890 --> 00:48:48.877
median income declined in
that time period 20 points.

00:48:53.750 --> 00:48:57.912
High school diploma or some
college, 13-point decline.

00:49:02.250 --> 00:49:06.460
And then advanced
degrees, 21-point rise.

00:49:06.460 --> 00:49:09.040
Bachelor's degrees,
16-point rise.

00:49:09.040 --> 00:49:12.430
This is a society
that's going like this,

00:49:12.430 --> 00:49:14.800
and that's what
we're dealing with.

00:49:14.800 --> 00:49:18.020
And arguably, it's
related to this.

00:49:25.080 --> 00:49:26.495
Let me move to Suzanne Berger.

00:49:31.900 --> 00:49:34.150
You should get to know her,
because she's around here,

00:49:34.150 --> 00:49:36.850
and she's really a
remarkable talent

00:49:36.850 --> 00:49:43.660
and has been a great
teacher for me.

00:49:43.660 --> 00:49:48.850
This is her 2005 book
called How We compete.

00:49:48.850 --> 00:49:52.060
And her essential point is that
there are different varieties

00:49:52.060 --> 00:49:52.780
of capitalism.

00:49:52.780 --> 00:49:56.350
We've been talking a
lot about that today.

00:49:56.350 --> 00:50:01.690
And the different approaches
emerged between the US

00:50:01.690 --> 00:50:06.700
and Asian economies in
advanced technology goods

00:50:06.700 --> 00:50:13.780
in this later part of the
1990s, early 2000s time period.

00:50:13.780 --> 00:50:15.070
So what's going on here?

00:50:15.070 --> 00:50:21.490
IT is a driver,
and codeable specs

00:50:21.490 --> 00:50:26.050
tied to computer-driven
equipment

00:50:26.050 --> 00:50:34.270
is enabling a divorce between
production and design.

00:50:34.270 --> 00:50:41.790
So in the old time period,
in a prior time period,

00:50:41.790 --> 00:50:47.440
Suzanne argues that
manufacturing companies,

00:50:47.440 --> 00:50:52.020
production firms were a
lot like model airplanes.

00:50:52.020 --> 00:50:54.590
And you all probably
don't remember the era

00:50:54.590 --> 00:50:56.210
of plastic model airplanes.

00:50:56.210 --> 00:50:58.640
I do.

00:50:58.640 --> 00:51:03.710
But you'd get this
batch of plastic parts,

00:51:03.710 --> 00:51:08.410
and they never quite fit.

00:51:08.410 --> 00:51:11.450
You'd have to work them,
and you'd get glue all over,

00:51:11.450 --> 00:51:15.318
and the glue would spill over,
and it would just be a mess.

00:51:15.318 --> 00:51:17.360
And you try and clean up
the glue with a Kleenex,

00:51:17.360 --> 00:51:19.068
and the Kleenex would
stick to the model.

00:51:21.800 --> 00:51:24.170
And you'd put rubber bands
around it to try and get it

00:51:24.170 --> 00:51:27.140
to lock in place, and you'd
break the damn thing trying

00:51:27.140 --> 00:51:29.270
to get it fixed.

00:51:29.270 --> 00:51:33.170
That's what manufacturing
used to be like, she argues.

00:51:33.170 --> 00:51:38.540
And to manage, that you needed a
very integrated vertical system

00:51:38.540 --> 00:51:41.570
with all parts of that system
tied and connected together

00:51:41.570 --> 00:51:45.230
to get around the difficulty
of the production process.

00:51:45.230 --> 00:51:50.410
But with codeable IT-based specs
and computer-driven equipment,

00:51:50.410 --> 00:51:53.560
he moved to an era of LEGOs.

00:51:53.560 --> 00:51:55.650
It's all computer-driven.

00:51:55.650 --> 00:51:57.470
You're going to be
producing LEGOs,

00:51:57.470 --> 00:52:02.060
and they are always going
to snap perfectly in place.

00:52:02.060 --> 00:52:04.940
That's how the production
system changed,

00:52:04.940 --> 00:52:10.490
she argued, in these two--
from these two different eras.

00:52:10.490 --> 00:52:12.520
And the classic
example is the iPod.

00:52:15.860 --> 00:52:25.910
Apple was able to pick a mix
of MP3 best technologies,

00:52:25.910 --> 00:52:33.560
and they tied it to
a new software access

00:52:33.560 --> 00:52:38.900
system for music in database
form, as you all know.

00:52:38.900 --> 00:52:40.430
Now it's video, as well.

00:52:44.830 --> 00:52:49.220
A classic Apple move, right?

00:52:49.220 --> 00:52:53.030
The problem with MP3
players before Apple

00:52:53.030 --> 00:52:56.330
was that you had to
commit a crime in order

00:52:56.330 --> 00:52:57.560
to use the MP3 player.

00:52:57.560 --> 00:53:00.620
You were stealing
someone's music.

00:53:00.620 --> 00:53:03.620
And it was a criminal act.

00:53:03.620 --> 00:53:06.800
What kind of product forced
you to commit a criminal act?

00:53:06.800 --> 00:53:08.780
It's not a great product line.

00:53:08.780 --> 00:53:11.660
So Apple invents an
entirely different way

00:53:11.660 --> 00:53:13.790
of organizing the
music industry,

00:53:13.790 --> 00:53:20.270
but it ties it to existing
MP3 player technology,

00:53:20.270 --> 00:53:23.377
which it receives to perfect.

00:53:23.377 --> 00:53:24.460
How is it able to do this?

00:53:24.460 --> 00:53:26.180
It was able to do this in
a remarkably short period

00:53:26.180 --> 00:53:26.720
of time.

00:53:26.720 --> 00:53:29.090
It was a matter of months.

00:53:29.090 --> 00:53:33.190
So he figures out what the
optimal MP3 player technologies

00:53:33.190 --> 00:53:37.910
are, who is producing
them, and go to them

00:53:37.910 --> 00:53:40.710
and enter into contracts
with all over the world--

00:53:40.710 --> 00:53:43.820
particularly in China,
but elsewhere, as well.

00:53:43.820 --> 00:53:47.000
And it knows that they're
going to snap together

00:53:47.000 --> 00:53:54.470
like LEGOs in the end, because
they are using codeable specs

00:53:54.470 --> 00:53:56.960
on computer-driven equipment.

00:53:56.960 --> 00:54:00.800
So you can now distribute
your production model.

00:54:00.800 --> 00:54:04.610
So Apple doesn't-- can do
this in a matter of months.

00:54:04.610 --> 00:54:11.360
It doesn't have to go buy green
space outside Wilmington, North

00:54:11.360 --> 00:54:13.888
Carolina, or something,
and build a new factory,

00:54:13.888 --> 00:54:16.180
and get all the permitting,
and spend years doing this,

00:54:16.180 --> 00:54:19.430
and raise a billion
dollars to do it.

00:54:19.430 --> 00:54:22.170
Instead, it quickly
enters into a deal--

00:54:22.170 --> 00:54:24.920
a series of deals with
existing producers,

00:54:24.920 --> 00:54:28.738
but it knows that it can
bring the product back,

00:54:28.738 --> 00:54:30.530
because it's going to
be LEGOs, and they're

00:54:30.530 --> 00:54:33.240
going to snap into place.

00:54:33.240 --> 00:54:36.690
Amazing, absolutely amazing.

00:54:36.690 --> 00:54:45.580
And I was in Japan
in 2006, and--

00:54:45.580 --> 00:54:46.600
in January.

00:54:46.600 --> 00:54:50.410
I spent a wonderful day as
it was snowing in Kyoto,

00:54:50.410 --> 00:54:51.610
which was complete magical.

00:54:51.610 --> 00:54:53.470
But it was mostly back in Tokyo.

00:54:53.470 --> 00:54:59.020
And the headline in the leading
English language newspaper

00:54:59.020 --> 00:55:09.010
in Tokyo was "Apple sells 14
million iPods in two weeks;

00:55:09.010 --> 00:55:10.060
where is Sony!!"

00:55:15.760 --> 00:55:18.300
It was just a reality
that Apple had

00:55:18.300 --> 00:55:20.580
been able to spring to
this whole new product

00:55:20.580 --> 00:55:22.950
line in a remarkably
short period of time

00:55:22.950 --> 00:55:29.010
by using a digital dispersed
distributed production model.

00:55:29.010 --> 00:55:34.380
And it's pretty
irresistible, because you--

00:55:34.380 --> 00:55:36.680
that level of time
and investments

00:55:36.680 --> 00:55:38.550
you have to assemble
ahead of time

00:55:38.550 --> 00:55:40.330
makes this really
quite convenient.

00:55:40.330 --> 00:55:43.180
So lots of US firms
moved to this model,

00:55:43.180 --> 00:55:46.770
and they're technologically
enabled by these technological

00:55:46.770 --> 00:55:48.830
advances to do so.

00:55:48.830 --> 00:55:53.610
Now, Suzanne also goes on to
argue, hey, other people--

00:55:53.610 --> 00:55:56.400
and she's looking a group of
Asian countries and firms--

00:55:56.400 --> 00:55:58.230
are not necessarily doing this.

00:55:58.230 --> 00:56:03.960
So in Korea, Samsung continues
to control the key components.

00:56:03.960 --> 00:56:08.370
It allows a certain amount
of assembly offshore.

00:56:08.370 --> 00:56:10.740
In Japan, there's
a conscious effort

00:56:10.740 --> 00:56:15.510
to keep integrated
innovation model,

00:56:15.510 --> 00:56:18.490
and control all the
critical stages.

00:56:18.490 --> 00:56:20.340
So the risk in
the Apple model is

00:56:20.340 --> 00:56:22.950
that you're offshoring
your production capability,

00:56:22.950 --> 00:56:25.080
and a certain amount of
the innovation capability's

00:56:25.080 --> 00:56:27.360
going to follow.

00:56:27.360 --> 00:56:28.770
That's the risk.

00:56:28.770 --> 00:56:32.280
And to avoid that,
companies in Japan and Korea

00:56:32.280 --> 00:56:37.020
are moving in a very different
organizational model.

00:56:37.020 --> 00:56:41.430
Both models, she
argues, may well work.

00:56:41.430 --> 00:56:44.130
So these are varieties of
capitalism at play here.

00:56:44.130 --> 00:56:46.830
But the important thing
I want you to understand

00:56:46.830 --> 00:56:50.830
is that you can now,
for the first time

00:56:50.830 --> 00:56:53.950
historically, sever
production and design.

00:56:53.950 --> 00:56:57.310
And it's pretty
irresistible to do so,

00:56:57.310 --> 00:57:00.070
because you significantly
reduce your risk, and exposure,

00:57:00.070 --> 00:57:02.890
and your investment
levels upfront.

00:57:02.890 --> 00:57:06.460
So that's why, she
would argue, US firms

00:57:06.460 --> 00:57:09.430
tend to pursue this model.

00:57:09.430 --> 00:57:12.515
And we'll go to her
next book next week

00:57:12.515 --> 00:57:15.400
and discover why the model may
not necessarily be optimal.

00:57:15.400 --> 00:57:18.110
We'll hold that in
advance until next week.

00:57:18.110 --> 00:57:21.750
So who's got Suzanne?

00:57:21.750 --> 00:57:23.630
Let's go ahead then, Matthew.

00:57:23.630 --> 00:57:26.937
AUDIENCE: So in How We
Compete, basically they

00:57:26.937 --> 00:57:28.770
look at a whole bunch
of different companies

00:57:28.770 --> 00:57:33.090
in many different
industries and try

00:57:33.090 --> 00:57:36.360
to find what it is that
makes companies competitive.

00:57:36.360 --> 00:57:40.350
So they find that there's
no single paradigm.

00:57:40.350 --> 00:57:42.540
And one of the
key lines there is

00:57:42.540 --> 00:57:44.640
that there's no sunset
industries, just

00:57:44.640 --> 00:57:45.570
sunset strategies.

00:57:45.570 --> 00:57:48.603
So really, to be
competitive, what they found

00:57:48.603 --> 00:57:51.270
is that companies always need to
be questioning their processes,

00:57:51.270 --> 00:57:54.050
looking for ways to innovate.

00:57:54.050 --> 00:57:57.030
And then what I got out
of it were primarily

00:57:57.030 --> 00:57:58.220
two different balances.

00:57:58.220 --> 00:58:03.870
One is this idea of
intelligent offshoring, where

00:58:03.870 --> 00:58:09.450
maybe outsourcing all
of your manufacturing

00:58:09.450 --> 00:58:13.860
is not the best idea because
there are other costs involved

00:58:13.860 --> 00:58:17.850
with that, and can
create innovation

00:58:17.850 --> 00:58:20.970
gaps within your own country.

00:58:20.970 --> 00:58:23.550
And then the other
balance being with IP,

00:58:23.550 --> 00:58:29.700
and how do you create a
collaborative environment

00:58:29.700 --> 00:58:36.850
where that's conducive to
growth and development, but also

00:58:36.850 --> 00:58:39.322
protecting your IP,
so that you don't

00:58:39.322 --> 00:58:41.840
create your own competitor?

00:58:41.840 --> 00:58:44.320
And so I have some
questions here.

00:58:47.940 --> 00:58:49.820
I think one of the
first things is

00:58:49.820 --> 00:58:53.240
how do companies in
fiercely competitive sectors

00:58:53.240 --> 00:58:58.390
actually set themselves up
to constantly be innovating?

00:58:58.390 --> 00:59:01.050
It's a tough thing to do.

00:59:02.773 --> 00:59:04.940
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: Let me
underscore the importance

00:59:04.940 --> 00:59:06.170
of your question.

00:59:06.170 --> 00:59:08.510
The number of companies that
are a hundred years old you

00:59:08.510 --> 00:59:11.550
can probably
measure on one hand.

00:59:11.550 --> 00:59:15.950
They go through disruption,
and they change, and they die.

00:59:15.950 --> 00:59:18.773
Long-lasting, long-enduring
companies are rare.

00:59:18.773 --> 00:59:20.940
And it's retaining this
innovation capability that's

00:59:20.940 --> 00:59:23.273
so critical, so you're driving
at a really key question.

00:59:28.590 --> 00:59:31.590
AUDIENCE: When you mentioned
innovative firms, firms

00:59:31.590 --> 00:59:34.680
that keep staying at the head,
my first thought is Apple.

00:59:34.680 --> 00:59:39.310
and I think Apple's, what,
like 30 years old now?

00:59:39.310 --> 00:59:43.770
It hasn't even proven that
it can withstay the trend.

00:59:43.770 --> 00:59:46.740
So I'm trying to think of
something that is actually

00:59:46.740 --> 00:59:50.010
more than 50 years old
that has been consistently

00:59:50.010 --> 00:59:50.970
on top of things.

00:59:50.970 --> 00:59:53.577
AUDIENCE: I think Coke is
probably my favorite example.

00:59:53.577 --> 00:59:55.660
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: Coke's
one, and IBM's another.

00:59:55.660 --> 00:59:57.930
AUDIENCE: Yeah, and then IBM.

00:59:57.930 --> 01:00:02.100
I think IBM I know more about,
just because they developed

01:00:02.100 --> 01:00:05.650
as sort of in f wave--

01:00:05.650 --> 01:00:10.280
in the context of the US
was looking for answers

01:00:10.280 --> 01:00:11.730
in the semiconductor realm.

01:00:11.730 --> 01:00:14.700
But more importantly,
they had to deal

01:00:14.700 --> 01:00:17.030
with the whole advent
of personal computing,

01:00:17.030 --> 01:00:21.790
and then they shifted now
into more IT-based services.

01:00:21.790 --> 01:00:25.090
And so they just contract
out and solve your problems.

01:00:25.090 --> 01:00:28.020
And I think it's
like you have to be

01:00:28.020 --> 01:00:33.370
sensitive to these big
technological disruptions,

01:00:33.370 --> 01:00:37.110
and then ride the wave
or get out completely,

01:00:37.110 --> 01:00:43.860
and being able to shut down
kind of large sections of--

01:00:43.860 --> 01:00:46.200
it was previously
advantageous maybe for Kodak

01:00:46.200 --> 01:00:49.627
to use disposable cameras, but
now we have digital cameras.

01:00:49.627 --> 01:00:51.210
And so you have to
be able to be like,

01:00:51.210 --> 01:00:54.540
OK, we're going to
really radically change

01:00:54.540 --> 01:00:58.050
the course of our company
in order to sustain

01:00:58.050 --> 01:01:00.420
and stay alive.

01:01:00.420 --> 01:01:03.750
And that's a hard decision
to be able to make.

01:01:03.750 --> 01:01:09.360
And so I think the resistance
to change piece is probably

01:01:09.360 --> 01:01:15.690
differentiates your Cokes from
maybe your less long-lasting

01:01:15.690 --> 01:01:16.723
companies.

01:01:16.723 --> 01:01:18.390
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN:
And next week you're

01:01:18.390 --> 01:01:21.090
going to start to read
your textbook, which

01:01:21.090 --> 01:01:23.820
is about the difficulty
of innovation

01:01:23.820 --> 01:01:27.380
in complex established
legacy economic sectors.

01:01:27.380 --> 01:01:30.140
And that's a large part
of this [INAUDIBLE]

01:01:30.140 --> 01:01:34.352
answering your question.

01:01:34.352 --> 01:01:36.060
AUDIENCE: The question
too is, if there's

01:01:36.060 --> 01:01:38.988
these new capabilities and you
don't use them, somebody will.

01:01:38.988 --> 01:01:40.530
So it's kind of like
a Pandora's box,

01:01:40.530 --> 01:01:43.740
because I may not want to
change my whole supply chain

01:01:43.740 --> 01:01:48.660
and get rid of a ton of
jobs for my employees

01:01:48.660 --> 01:01:52.575
because of all the things
that happened after,

01:01:52.575 --> 01:01:54.450
but my competitor is
probably going to do it.

01:01:54.450 --> 01:01:57.083
And if I don't do it, then
he's going to have a lower--

01:01:57.083 --> 01:01:59.250
he's going to lower his
costs, and he'll most likely

01:01:59.250 --> 01:02:00.810
beat me to market.

01:02:00.810 --> 01:02:04.170
And there's a quote from
Andrew Carnegie, where

01:02:04.170 --> 01:02:06.450
he goes like, you should
always use the best tools,

01:02:06.450 --> 01:02:09.960
even if it's very hard
to cheat your old tools.

01:02:09.960 --> 01:02:14.418
Because as a titan of industry,
if you don't, somebody else

01:02:14.418 --> 01:02:14.918
will.

01:02:19.090 --> 01:02:21.090
AUDIENCE: And the other
thing I liked from Hayes

01:02:21.090 --> 01:02:21.715
I think about--

01:02:21.715 --> 01:02:25.490
I know it goes a little bit
into next week's readings here,

01:02:25.490 --> 01:02:29.910
but to what extent do you think
that design and manufacturing

01:02:29.910 --> 01:02:33.030
can actually be separated?

01:02:33.030 --> 01:02:35.160
I know here at MIT, in
the mechanical engineering

01:02:35.160 --> 01:02:39.870
department, there's still
a big emphasis on taking

01:02:39.870 --> 01:02:43.380
the manufacturing classes, in
terms of just understanding

01:02:43.380 --> 01:02:45.240
when you're designing,
what is feasible,

01:02:45.240 --> 01:02:48.800
what is possible to manufacture.

01:02:48.800 --> 01:02:52.220
Maybe 3D printing, it's a
little bit more separate.

01:02:52.220 --> 01:02:55.620
You're basically
saying can be made.

01:02:55.620 --> 01:03:00.570
But there's a lot of
know-how embodied in having

01:03:00.570 --> 01:03:03.660
the manufacturing there too.

01:03:03.660 --> 01:03:06.220
I don't fully think
that they can be--

01:03:06.220 --> 01:03:09.510
or it's wise to
fully separate them.

01:03:09.510 --> 01:03:13.060
I want to see if people also
have some more thoughts there.

01:03:13.060 --> 01:03:16.950
AUDIENCE: I was going to say
that maybe the separation is

01:03:16.950 --> 01:03:19.260
just a figment of
our imaginations,

01:03:19.260 --> 01:03:22.050
because I know that
when Suzanne Berger was

01:03:22.050 --> 01:03:24.480
on the panel in
bootcamp course--

01:03:24.480 --> 01:03:28.320
I think it was Suzanne who
said that the people who--

01:03:28.320 --> 01:03:34.470
the designers for Apple spend
most of their time not here.

01:03:34.470 --> 01:03:36.990
They spend their time in
the offshore manufacturing.

01:03:36.990 --> 01:03:38.005
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN:
Shenzhen, in particular.

01:03:38.005 --> 01:03:39.182
AUDIENCE: Makes sense.

01:03:39.182 --> 01:03:40.890
AUDIENCE: So they're
not really separate,

01:03:40.890 --> 01:03:43.500
although they're quote,
unquote "separate."

01:03:43.500 --> 01:03:49.440
AUDIENCE: I think also
objective is important.

01:03:49.440 --> 01:03:51.240
And if you're
trying to separate,

01:03:51.240 --> 01:03:53.370
what are you trying to
separate in order to do--

01:03:53.370 --> 01:03:56.382
if you're trying to separate
in order to cut costs,

01:03:56.382 --> 01:03:58.590
you'll find a way, because
it'll be more advantageous

01:03:58.590 --> 01:04:01.500
for you to send your
manufacturing section over,

01:04:01.500 --> 01:04:02.280
if you're Apple.

01:04:02.280 --> 01:04:03.960
But even if you do
that, you're going

01:04:03.960 --> 01:04:07.080
to have to send your designers
in order to do the next thing

01:04:07.080 --> 01:04:09.870
and really consider how
am I going to manufacture

01:04:09.870 --> 01:04:11.120
this thing that I've designed.

01:04:11.120 --> 01:04:13.500
And in order to do that,
you can't separate them.

01:04:13.500 --> 01:04:15.600
So the mechanical engineering
department, I think,

01:04:15.600 --> 01:04:17.880
is probably pretty
smart by training--

01:04:17.880 --> 01:04:20.340
when training all mechanical
engineers who are then

01:04:20.340 --> 01:04:21.972
going to go up design
and manufacture,

01:04:21.972 --> 01:04:24.180
even though you might
specialize in one or the other,

01:04:24.180 --> 01:04:26.570
you need to have a strong
basis and a foundation of both,

01:04:26.570 --> 01:04:28.410
and understandable
are critical in order

01:04:28.410 --> 01:04:33.120
to do anything that's probably
long-lasting or meaningful,

01:04:33.120 --> 01:04:34.852
and I guess quote,
unquote "innovative."

01:04:38.290 --> 01:04:40.690
AUDIENCE: When we talk about
design, what do we mean?

01:04:40.690 --> 01:04:43.030
Do we mean the designer
of an industrial system?

01:04:43.030 --> 01:04:45.370
Do we mean the designer of
an industrial appliance?

01:04:45.370 --> 01:04:46.870
Do we mean the
designer of hardware?

01:04:46.870 --> 01:04:48.140
Do we mean the
designer of software?

01:04:48.140 --> 01:04:50.110
What components of
design are we concerned

01:04:50.110 --> 01:04:53.620
about, and in what ways is this
relevant in the conversation

01:04:53.620 --> 01:04:56.710
we're having right now
about integrative innovation

01:04:56.710 --> 01:04:57.703
processes?

01:05:01.090 --> 01:05:05.370
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] I'm
viewing it, when we see--

01:05:05.370 --> 01:05:07.350
we're comparing the
design and manufacturing,

01:05:07.350 --> 01:05:09.540
so I wouldn't think of
it so much as software.

01:05:09.540 --> 01:05:12.180
Primarily hardware,
where the design

01:05:12.180 --> 01:05:19.420
may be having a 3D model or
a layout of my circuit board

01:05:19.420 --> 01:05:21.540
that I'm going to
send to a manufacturer

01:05:21.540 --> 01:05:23.730
on the other side of the
world, who will actually

01:05:23.730 --> 01:05:26.544
make those components, put them
together, and send them back

01:05:26.544 --> 01:05:27.930
to me.

01:05:27.930 --> 01:05:30.605
That's at least
what I [INAUDIBLE]..

01:05:30.605 --> 01:05:31.230
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

01:05:31.230 --> 01:05:34.130
I guess I raise that concern
because, as a designer myself--

01:05:34.130 --> 01:05:36.320
I think of myself as
a design researcher,

01:05:36.320 --> 01:05:38.390
because I think about
the ways in which you

01:05:38.390 --> 01:05:42.200
can take systems engineering
approaches to social issues.

01:05:42.200 --> 01:05:46.100
And there's a big
debate right now

01:05:46.100 --> 01:05:49.230
in the design community
about what design even is.

01:05:49.230 --> 01:05:51.410
There's this big debate
about design thinking

01:05:51.410 --> 01:05:54.450
and versus the design cycle,
and who gets to create it.

01:05:54.450 --> 01:05:57.860
And there's even more of
a debate about the nuances

01:05:57.860 --> 01:06:02.690
and exerting the power
in creating something.

01:06:02.690 --> 01:06:05.720
All of these hardware choices
are political choices,

01:06:05.720 --> 01:06:08.930
and they have impacts on
both the user and the society

01:06:08.930 --> 01:06:10.500
in which they're implemented.

01:06:10.500 --> 01:06:13.130
So that's why I think it's
important to really consider,

01:06:13.130 --> 01:06:16.340
when both the author and we
talk about design, what kind

01:06:16.340 --> 01:06:19.310
of design we're talking about,
and we view it not necessarily

01:06:19.310 --> 01:06:23.360
as a neutral and apolitical
action, but very much

01:06:23.360 --> 01:06:28.880
as a reflection of what
that corporation values

01:06:28.880 --> 01:06:35.510
and what kind of values they
want to promote in a society.

01:06:35.510 --> 01:06:39.590
When I look at this laptop, I
don't think, this is beautiful,

01:06:39.590 --> 01:06:41.600
this is elegant,
this is functional.

01:06:41.600 --> 01:06:44.390
I think, this is how this
company wants the world

01:06:44.390 --> 01:06:51.270
to look like, and this is
their long-lasting and material

01:06:51.270 --> 01:06:56.375
vision for what the world could
look like for the long run.

01:06:56.375 --> 01:06:58.750
AUDIENCE: Alternatively, I
think a lot of design thinking

01:06:58.750 --> 01:07:01.408
actually is for companies
that, while we're

01:07:01.408 --> 01:07:03.450
looking at what they--
what we think their vision

01:07:03.450 --> 01:07:05.418
is [INAUDIBLE] when we
look at, say, a Macbook,

01:07:05.418 --> 01:07:06.960
I think a lot of
them are looking to,

01:07:06.960 --> 01:07:09.522
and most designers
at Apple would say,

01:07:09.522 --> 01:07:11.730
in their design process,
they're looking at the users

01:07:11.730 --> 01:07:13.855
and seeing what the
users actually want.

01:07:13.855 --> 01:07:17.650
[INAUDIBLE] there's a
lot of looking both ways.

01:07:17.650 --> 01:07:19.480
AUDIENCE: From a
capitalist perspective,

01:07:19.480 --> 01:07:21.078
the way I would
look at it is, OK,

01:07:21.078 --> 01:07:22.620
what are the
manufacturing abilities?

01:07:22.620 --> 01:07:24.382
How much does it cost me?

01:07:24.382 --> 01:07:25.590
How long is it going to take?

01:07:25.590 --> 01:07:26.970
What are going to be the issues?

01:07:26.970 --> 01:07:28.117
Don't make it complicated.

01:07:28.117 --> 01:07:29.700
Simplify it, simplify
it, simplify it,

01:07:29.700 --> 01:07:32.033
because in execution, it's
going to be way more complex,

01:07:32.033 --> 01:07:34.030
and I'm not trying
to deal with that.

01:07:34.030 --> 01:07:35.970
And then, OK, I'll make it.

01:07:35.970 --> 01:07:38.220
Make sure it's slightly
different than my competitors.

01:07:38.220 --> 01:07:40.110
Make sure it follows
the values of my company

01:07:40.110 --> 01:07:41.040
in a certain amount of way.

01:07:41.040 --> 01:07:42.450
And then when I
market it, you think

01:07:42.450 --> 01:07:43.950
it's something more
than it actually

01:07:43.950 --> 01:07:46.841
is because then you'll buy it,
because it's worth the value.

01:07:50.500 --> 01:07:54.190
AUDIENCE: I think maybe
American Apparel and--

01:07:54.190 --> 01:07:56.410
they hinted at American
Apparel, Lucky Brand Jeans,

01:07:56.410 --> 01:08:00.380
and some other companies
that are very heavy--

01:08:00.380 --> 01:08:02.380
or their models are
particularly because they're

01:08:02.380 --> 01:08:03.047
based in the US.

01:08:03.047 --> 01:08:06.740
And even though it might be
less expensive to like build

01:08:06.740 --> 01:08:11.230
and manufacture your jeans or
your t-shirts, for example,

01:08:11.230 --> 01:08:16.180
outside of Los Angeles,
you lose other factors,

01:08:16.180 --> 01:08:19.960
which is being able to say made
in the USA, blah, blah, blah.

01:08:19.960 --> 01:08:24.580
But also you gain production
speak and all of these things

01:08:24.580 --> 01:08:27.486
that Martin was talking
about from coupling

01:08:27.486 --> 01:08:29.319
these design and the
manufacturing processes

01:08:29.319 --> 01:08:30.300
and leaving them here.

01:08:30.300 --> 01:08:33.160
But at the end of
the day, I think

01:08:33.160 --> 01:08:34.720
you do a cost benefit
analysis, kind

01:08:34.720 --> 01:08:37.779
of like Martin said,
and then just make sure

01:08:37.779 --> 01:08:42.500
that your company values
is in line with the product

01:08:42.500 --> 01:08:45.640
and how you want people to
interface with the world

01:08:45.640 --> 01:08:46.667
through your product.

01:08:46.667 --> 01:08:48.250
AUDIENCE: But then
going off that, I'm

01:08:48.250 --> 01:08:50.140
curious how much
of an advantages

01:08:50.140 --> 01:08:52.500
that you get from
producing in the US can--

01:08:52.500 --> 01:08:56.319
or whatever their gimmick is--

01:08:56.319 --> 01:08:58.990
how long those will last.

01:08:58.990 --> 01:09:01.210
Like American Apparel just
closed all their stores.

01:09:01.210 --> 01:09:05.020
So does that mean that that
approach isn't sustainable

01:09:05.020 --> 01:09:11.020
and that they should have taken
another look at outsourcing?

01:09:11.020 --> 01:09:13.600
There are other factors
contributing to it,

01:09:13.600 --> 01:09:16.210
but is that--

01:09:16.210 --> 01:09:18.100
do these companies have
to pick what society

01:09:18.100 --> 01:09:21.771
will want as their
special sauce,

01:09:21.771 --> 01:09:23.229
and hope that it
lasts long enough,

01:09:23.229 --> 01:09:25.689
or are they eventually
going to need to think

01:09:25.689 --> 01:09:27.441
about these alternatives?

01:09:27.441 --> 01:09:29.899
AUDIENCE: They definitely should
consider the alternatives,

01:09:29.899 --> 01:09:31.492
but when--

01:09:31.492 --> 01:09:33.700
at least with American
Apparel, like you were saying,

01:09:33.700 --> 01:09:35.117
there's probably
a ton of factors.

01:09:35.117 --> 01:09:36.880
And I think just to
answer that question,

01:09:36.880 --> 01:09:38.350
we just need more data.

01:09:38.350 --> 01:09:41.380
So we need to somehow control
for the type of industry,

01:09:41.380 --> 01:09:44.729
the time period, the location,
