01:11:45.100 --> 01:11:46.420
What we're going to do
is we're going to find

01:11:46.420 --> 01:11:47.628
a very cheap way of doing it.

01:11:47.628 --> 01:11:51.190
They have it on the market
by two weeks pretty much.

01:11:51.190 --> 01:11:54.130
They like rapidly design and
they go for a low price point,

01:11:54.130 --> 01:11:56.630
and then they'll put
it into the market,

01:11:56.630 --> 01:11:59.293
and then people will buy it.

01:11:59.293 --> 01:12:00.460
You're not buying for value.

01:12:00.460 --> 01:12:01.630
You're buying because
this is trendy,

01:12:01.630 --> 01:12:03.170
and I don't want to spend much.

01:12:03.170 --> 01:12:05.320
And that's kind of their
value prop right now.

01:12:05.320 --> 01:12:07.540
because they're usually
slightly more than H&M,

01:12:07.540 --> 01:12:09.467
but it's just that
right model for I

01:12:09.467 --> 01:12:11.050
want to buy a good
amount, and I don't

01:12:11.050 --> 01:12:14.250
want to look like I'm
from 10 years ago.

01:12:14.250 --> 01:12:16.250
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: Does
that sound right, Lily?

01:12:16.250 --> 01:12:17.300
OK.

01:12:17.300 --> 01:12:19.200
AUDIENCE: But yeah, I would
have to look at the data of how

01:12:19.200 --> 01:12:19.900
their sales reflected.

01:12:19.900 --> 01:12:21.330
Because I think
some people do care,

01:12:21.330 --> 01:12:22.705
or they might act
like they care,

01:12:22.705 --> 01:12:25.278
but probably when they
vote with their dollar--

01:12:25.278 --> 01:12:26.820
because there's Zara
and there's H&M,

01:12:26.820 --> 01:12:28.470
but there's not too
much of a difference.

01:12:28.470 --> 01:12:30.303
And I'm pretty sure
they different products.

01:12:30.303 --> 01:12:32.460
So somebody might be
like, I really like

01:12:32.460 --> 01:12:36.392
this sweater from Zara, so
I'll definitely go that way.

01:12:36.392 --> 01:12:38.850
I would debate that there's a
very small percentage that'll

01:12:38.850 --> 01:12:41.480
be like, I'm totally never going
to buy from the store again--

01:12:41.480 --> 01:12:43.438
or I'm totally not going
to buy from this store

01:12:43.438 --> 01:12:46.190
again, and then not
go back to buying

01:12:46.190 --> 01:12:47.535
from like two weeks later.

01:12:47.535 --> 01:12:49.910
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: So I'm
going to bring us back to Mac,

01:12:49.910 --> 01:12:52.930
since we've now gone off
to into the fashion world--

01:12:52.930 --> 01:12:54.260
back to some more fundamental.

01:12:54.260 --> 01:12:55.350
Do you have some
closing points you

01:12:55.350 --> 01:12:56.642
want to make on Suzanne's book?

01:12:56.642 --> 01:12:59.687
What do you think
is really key in it?

01:12:59.687 --> 01:13:01.770
AUDIENCE: I think one real
key point that maybe we

01:13:01.770 --> 01:13:05.520
didn't get as much to
talk on is that maybe we

01:13:05.520 --> 01:13:10.890
have, as Americans, this
idea of a birthright to being

01:13:10.890 --> 01:13:15.660
at the forefront of
innovation, and really

01:13:15.660 --> 01:13:20.520
pointing out that no one
who's completed and sitting

01:13:20.520 --> 01:13:24.960
on their laurels will
stay in that position.

01:13:24.960 --> 01:13:28.400
I think there's a good
contrast between her ideas

01:13:28.400 --> 01:13:32.278
on outsourcing versus Berger's.

01:13:32.278 --> 01:13:33.618
Something to think about.

01:13:33.618 --> 01:13:34.660
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: Good.

01:13:34.660 --> 01:13:37.850
Good point, Matthew.

01:13:37.850 --> 01:13:42.140
All right, that brings us
to our closing reading.

01:13:47.310 --> 01:13:52.590
This is one of MIT's great
provosts, Joel Moses,

01:13:52.590 --> 01:13:56.850
who was deeply
involved in the early

01:13:56.850 --> 01:14:00.150
and, indeed, later stages
of the computing revolution.

01:14:00.150 --> 01:14:04.470
So this is a young Joel
at project MAC at MIT,

01:14:04.470 --> 01:14:08.880
which is MIT's
implementation engine

01:14:08.880 --> 01:14:12.810
for a lot of the early
computing advances.

01:14:12.810 --> 01:14:16.800
So Joel steps back and
writes this fun piece, which

01:14:16.800 --> 01:14:19.950
I wanted to throw
in here at the end,

01:14:19.950 --> 01:14:25.110
to pick up our determinism
theme one more time.

01:14:25.110 --> 01:14:27.360
We've been talking about
different kinds of innovation

01:14:27.360 --> 01:14:29.250
systems and how
different countries have

01:14:29.250 --> 01:14:31.140
varieties of capitalism
and varieties

01:14:31.140 --> 01:14:33.060
of innovation systems.

01:14:33.060 --> 01:14:37.610
And Joel takes us back
a step and gives us more

01:14:37.610 --> 01:14:42.530
of a 10,000-foot kind
of look, which I was--

01:14:42.530 --> 01:14:45.590
I've always been intrigued with.

01:14:45.590 --> 01:14:51.560
He argues that there are three
fundamentally different design

01:14:51.560 --> 01:14:52.340
methodologies.

01:14:52.340 --> 01:14:56.450
So this is a design methodology
in a societal sense,

01:14:56.450 --> 01:14:59.120
rather than engineering design,
that Matthew was leading us

01:14:59.120 --> 01:15:01.910
through earlier.

01:15:01.910 --> 01:15:04.610
And he argues that,
historically, the US

01:15:04.610 --> 01:15:09.920
has used what he calls
a tree and branch

01:15:09.920 --> 01:15:13.310
organizational
attempt, which creates

01:15:13.310 --> 01:15:16.640
very hierarchical firms.

01:15:16.640 --> 01:15:23.030
And he argues that this
very hierarchical system--

01:15:23.030 --> 01:15:27.470
and you can picture with the
organization chart looks--

01:15:27.470 --> 01:15:32.390
it's like a tree, top
management all the way down

01:15:32.390 --> 01:15:36.350
through many different
hierarchies of levels--

01:15:36.350 --> 01:15:38.840
that that fits a mass
production company.

01:15:38.840 --> 01:15:42.342
This is the kind of economy
that was compelled coming out

01:15:42.342 --> 01:15:43.550
of the Industrial Revolution.

01:15:46.690 --> 01:15:49.540
And it's organized
for manufacturing

01:15:49.540 --> 01:15:54.820
at a national scale for
national markets, where

01:15:54.820 --> 01:15:57.490
a lot of vertical
integration is required.

01:15:57.490 --> 01:16:00.970
So think about the big
three US car companies.

01:16:00.970 --> 01:16:03.880
Now, then he makes an
interesting additional point,

01:16:03.880 --> 01:16:10.240
which is this, by the way,
fits an Aristotelian hierarchy

01:16:10.240 --> 01:16:13.210
of ordered knowledge.

01:16:13.210 --> 01:16:19.630
This is the way in which Western
thought organizes science.

01:16:19.630 --> 01:16:21.310
That's what Aristotle
is doing, he's

01:16:21.310 --> 01:16:23.030
creating these tree
and branch systems.

01:16:23.030 --> 01:16:27.880
Surprise, it shows up in
industrial organization

01:16:27.880 --> 01:16:29.560
in the West.

01:16:29.560 --> 01:16:33.220
But he argues that the
tree and branch hierarchy

01:16:33.220 --> 01:16:38.260
means tremendous inflexibility
and great difficulty

01:16:38.260 --> 01:16:40.810
in managing change,
because you've

01:16:40.810 --> 01:16:43.570
got to bring all those
different systems, all

01:16:43.570 --> 01:16:48.100
those different levels in the
line in order to pursue change.

01:16:48.100 --> 01:16:54.770
So the second design
methodology is around what

01:16:54.770 --> 01:16:56.270
he calls a layered system.

01:16:56.270 --> 01:17:00.860
And he argues that Japan's
incredible success of the '70s

01:17:00.860 --> 01:17:05.000
and '80s is not just the
different industrial model,

01:17:05.000 --> 01:17:08.360
a quality production model.

01:17:08.360 --> 01:17:09.860
It's deeper than that.

01:17:09.860 --> 01:17:11.510
There's a whole
social organization

01:17:11.510 --> 01:17:14.720
set of issues that's
coming with it.

01:17:14.720 --> 01:17:17.270
And [INAUDIBLE],, you
were driving towards some

01:17:17.270 --> 01:17:20.210
of these points, I think.

01:17:20.210 --> 01:17:31.290
So in Japan's system, there
are separate layered levels,

01:17:31.290 --> 01:17:35.040
and you tend to move
through your career

01:17:35.040 --> 01:17:37.440
with your age cohort.

01:17:37.440 --> 01:17:41.700
And as a group, you move
from level to level.

01:17:41.700 --> 01:17:46.110
And there's obviously
several levels here.

01:17:46.110 --> 01:17:49.020
It's much less tree and
branch hierarchical.

01:17:49.020 --> 01:17:54.270
It is pretty flat
within that age cohort.

01:17:54.270 --> 01:17:58.470
And you tend to know that you're
going to move with your level

01:17:58.470 --> 01:18:00.540
into successive position.

01:18:00.540 --> 01:18:06.960
So it forces a significant
amount of consensus.

01:18:06.960 --> 01:18:13.470
So Joel's interesting comparison
is this is Plato's Republic--

01:18:13.470 --> 01:18:16.860
the philosopher king, the
guardians, the citizens--

01:18:16.860 --> 01:18:18.690
those are kind of layers.

01:18:18.690 --> 01:18:25.230
So not an Aristotelian,
but a Platonic model.

01:18:25.230 --> 01:18:29.580
And then he says
there's a third.

01:18:29.580 --> 01:18:36.690
And this is the network model
that the US nurtured coming out

01:18:36.690 --> 01:18:42.390
of the IT revolution, which
is much flatter, much less

01:18:42.390 --> 01:18:44.100
hierarchical.

01:18:44.100 --> 01:18:48.480
Not even layered--
it's pretty flat.

01:18:48.480 --> 01:18:53.520
And it's driven by the
collaborative group innovation

01:18:53.520 --> 01:18:58.905
systems that are required
for the development of the IT

01:18:58.905 --> 01:19:01.030
sector--

01:19:01.030 --> 01:19:02.910
that a rigid tree
and branch hierarchy

01:19:02.910 --> 01:19:07.260
is just not going to work
in that IT world, which

01:19:07.260 --> 01:19:08.940
requires a tremendous
amount of almost

01:19:08.940 --> 01:19:11.820
democratization of workforce.

01:19:11.820 --> 01:19:16.260
So back, Martin, to
your Andy Grove analogy,

01:19:16.260 --> 01:19:19.860
when the leaders of Intel--

01:19:19.860 --> 01:19:24.750
when Bob Noyce, and Grove, and
Gordon Moore were setting up

01:19:24.750 --> 01:19:30.120
Intel, there are no offices.

01:19:30.120 --> 01:19:31.770
Everybody's got a
cubicle, including

01:19:31.770 --> 01:19:33.200
Noyce, and Moore, and Grove.

01:19:42.900 --> 01:19:45.300
The network model, Joel
argues, is actually

01:19:45.300 --> 01:19:47.610
much faster, and
much more flexible,

01:19:47.610 --> 01:19:52.260
and much more subject to change
than even the layered model

01:19:52.260 --> 01:19:53.760
that Japan brings about.

01:19:53.760 --> 01:19:56.340
And so you start
thinking here, gee, it's

01:19:56.340 --> 01:19:59.550
no wonder the US
auto industry got

01:19:59.550 --> 01:20:04.110
rolled when it came up
against Japan's layered model.

01:20:04.110 --> 01:20:06.810
And then you start thinking,
oh, no wonder Japan

01:20:06.810 --> 01:20:09.300
missed the IT revolution,
if the organizational model

01:20:09.300 --> 01:20:10.633
required this network.

01:20:10.633 --> 01:20:12.300
Now, look, these are
highly speculative.

01:20:12.300 --> 01:20:14.337
We'll never prove these.

01:20:14.337 --> 01:20:16.170
They're really only for
discussion purposes.

01:20:16.170 --> 01:20:19.450
All of us know that are more
complex stories behind it.

01:20:19.450 --> 01:20:24.030
But I think there is an
idea about the relationship

01:20:24.030 --> 01:20:28.200
between social
organization and the kind

01:20:28.200 --> 01:20:31.710
of industrial developments that
your society is going through,

01:20:31.710 --> 01:20:36.330
and the kind of organizational
models that those compel.

01:20:36.330 --> 01:20:42.430
Joel's great complaint
is that engineering

01:20:42.430 --> 01:20:48.780
lacks the models
to be able to grasp

01:20:48.780 --> 01:20:50.730
these different
organizational structures,

01:20:50.730 --> 01:20:54.750
that you can't really fit
that within a traditional kind

01:20:54.750 --> 01:20:58.800
of engineering analysis, and
that engineering, therefore,

01:20:58.800 --> 01:21:01.230
needs to rethink this.

01:21:01.230 --> 01:21:02.850
That's part of the
reason why he's

01:21:02.850 --> 01:21:07.950
a major leader of MIT's
Engineering Systems

01:21:07.950 --> 01:21:11.700
Division, which, of course,
has now been closed.

01:21:11.700 --> 01:21:14.640
But that's part of what Joel
and some of his colleagues

01:21:14.640 --> 01:21:18.360
are trying to do, when
they set up BSD at MIT.

01:21:24.910 --> 01:21:28.080
I just want to close out
by saying that there's

01:21:28.080 --> 01:21:29.830
another thing that
we'll need to consider,

01:21:29.830 --> 01:21:31.810
as we move into
next week's class--

01:21:31.810 --> 01:21:34.600
that the whole
nature of competition

01:21:34.600 --> 01:21:39.190
is changing in manufacturing,
that it's no longer

01:21:39.190 --> 01:21:41.260
a world of manufacturing
goods, it's

01:21:41.260 --> 01:21:43.570
a world of
manufactured goods that

01:21:43.570 --> 01:21:48.610
are fused with IT technologies
that, in turn, are

01:21:48.610 --> 01:21:50.180
service delivery models.

01:21:50.180 --> 01:21:54.700
So there's a whole fusion of
services and manufacturing

01:21:54.700 --> 01:21:57.130
going on that makes some of
the stories we've been talking

01:21:57.130 --> 01:21:59.170
about today more complicated.

01:22:01.770 --> 01:22:04.680
In past decades, the
story was quality.

01:22:04.680 --> 01:22:07.620
Now, there's a whole
level of customization,

01:22:07.620 --> 01:22:10.140
and speed, and
customer responsiveness

01:22:10.140 --> 01:22:12.990
that we have to
think about, as well.

01:22:12.990 --> 01:22:14.730
And your ability to
get on top of those,

01:22:14.730 --> 01:22:18.300
as well as on
quality, becomes key.

01:22:18.300 --> 01:22:20.370
It's not simply the
best technology,

01:22:20.370 --> 01:22:24.750
but it's the best technology
plus the best business models

01:22:24.750 --> 01:22:29.410
and delivery models that
have to be thought about.

01:22:29.410 --> 01:22:32.550
There used to be traded
goods, traded product.

01:22:32.550 --> 01:22:36.180
Now, there's traded all
kinds of knowledge management

01:22:36.180 --> 01:22:39.180
and services that are tied
to these products that

01:22:39.180 --> 01:22:45.040
becomes critical factors
in your ability to compete.

01:22:45.040 --> 01:22:47.620
In the past, it was the
workforce skills side.

01:22:47.620 --> 01:22:52.130
Now, it's much more continuous
learning in your workforce.

01:22:52.130 --> 01:22:54.320
Then it was low cost of capital.

01:22:54.320 --> 01:22:58.510
Now, it's efficiency in
all the financial services

01:22:58.510 --> 01:23:02.080
stages that you've got to
get through the hurdles of,

01:23:02.080 --> 01:23:06.300
not just the initial
capital cost.

01:23:06.300 --> 01:23:09.800
And there's a whole evolution
of intangible capital, as well.

01:23:09.800 --> 01:23:12.940
So there's a whole
new set of factors

01:23:12.940 --> 01:23:16.900
that's coming into the
manufacturing world, that we've

01:23:16.900 --> 01:23:20.380
only started to glimpse
from today's discussion.

01:23:20.380 --> 01:23:25.530
But let's go back to Joel
and his three models.

01:23:25.530 --> 01:23:27.370
Chris, it's all yours.

01:23:27.370 --> 01:23:31.000
AUDIENCE: So to
summarize, Joel is

01:23:31.000 --> 01:23:33.850
presenting these three models--

01:23:33.850 --> 01:23:35.740
the hierarchical
decomposition model,

01:23:35.740 --> 01:23:39.670
where it's the branch tree
structure, the network design

01:23:39.670 --> 01:23:44.590
model, and then the
layered design model.

01:23:44.590 --> 01:23:48.070
And then he basically goes on
to outline a bunch of examples

01:23:48.070 --> 01:23:49.510
where you could present--

01:23:49.510 --> 01:23:52.870
or sorry, apply
different methodologies

01:23:52.870 --> 01:23:54.730
into analyzing various systems.

01:23:54.730 --> 01:23:58.540
So he goes through a
philosophy example,

01:23:58.540 --> 01:24:03.500
he goes through manufacturing,
even more science-based--

01:24:03.500 --> 01:24:05.890
so like the models of
the human mind and body.

01:24:05.890 --> 01:24:08.860
And one of them I found
particularly interesting

01:24:08.860 --> 01:24:11.350
was where he brought
up culture, and how

01:24:11.350 --> 01:24:14.920
preconceptions of how
engineering and manufacturing

01:24:14.920 --> 01:24:17.470
is viewed here
versus, let's say,

01:24:17.470 --> 01:24:21.820
Germany or Japan has
really impacted the way

01:24:21.820 --> 01:24:24.400
these countries have
responded towards shifts

01:24:24.400 --> 01:24:28.690
in manufacturing, and how that
industry develops-- and also

01:24:28.690 --> 01:24:31.090
how cooperation in
Japanese culture

01:24:31.090 --> 01:24:34.660
has really allowed
the precipitous rise

01:24:34.660 --> 01:24:38.800
of their industry and
manufacturing capabilities,

01:24:38.800 --> 01:24:42.640
and how that shaped and kind
of forced American firms

01:24:42.640 --> 01:24:47.585
to adopt a similar structure
or methodology in order

01:24:47.585 --> 01:24:48.085
to compete.

01:24:51.250 --> 01:24:53.080
Interestingly enough,
a lot of the examples

01:24:53.080 --> 01:24:54.640
were not really
engineering-based,

01:24:54.640 --> 01:24:59.770
even though he started from the
hierarchical model, which is

01:24:59.770 --> 01:25:01.810
seen very often in engineering.

01:25:01.810 --> 01:25:03.910
And I thought that was
really interesting.

01:25:03.910 --> 01:25:06.790
And we can definitely go
into some of the examples

01:25:06.790 --> 01:25:09.790
more, if anyone has a
particular one to go into.

01:25:09.790 --> 01:25:13.090
But to start off the discussion.

01:25:13.090 --> 01:25:15.430
I thought this question
was really interesting.

01:25:15.430 --> 01:25:18.190
How does a country shift
from a tree structure--

01:25:18.190 --> 01:25:20.020
so the hierarchy one--

01:25:20.020 --> 01:25:22.120
to a more layered or
network structure,

01:25:22.120 --> 01:25:25.490
once it's already
been established?

01:25:25.490 --> 01:25:29.050
So if there's any thoughts,
feel free to throw them out.

01:25:29.050 --> 01:25:31.030
AUDIENCE: So I
took a class called

01:25:31.030 --> 01:25:33.150
structural organizations,
and it talks about--

01:25:33.150 --> 01:25:35.192
so it's not like there's
a right or wrong answer.

01:25:35.192 --> 01:25:37.220
It just really depends
what you're trying to do.

01:25:37.220 --> 01:25:38.275
So in general, it's
more networked,

01:25:38.275 --> 01:25:40.300
it means you want to
make better decisions.

01:25:40.300 --> 01:25:42.908
But the drawback is it'll
take a much longer time.

01:25:42.908 --> 01:25:44.950
Hierarchical, you might
not make great decisions,

01:25:44.950 --> 01:25:46.367
but you'll make
them very quickly.

01:25:46.367 --> 01:25:49.360
And as long as people
respect the person who's

01:25:49.360 --> 01:25:52.372
making the decision, it turns
out to be pretty much OK.

01:25:52.372 --> 01:25:54.580
In terms of a company, I
think it really does depend,

01:25:54.580 --> 01:25:57.730
because I think the
network structure works

01:25:57.730 --> 01:25:59.340
great for like a
Facebook or something

01:25:59.340 --> 01:26:01.840
with internet base, where you're
really competing for ideas,

01:26:01.840 --> 01:26:03.715
you're trying to come
up with the best ideas.

01:26:03.715 --> 01:26:06.010
Things move quickly, so you
want to iterate quickly.

01:26:06.010 --> 01:26:07.195
Versus, I think, if
it was manufacturing,

01:26:07.195 --> 01:26:08.426
I wouldn't want that as much.

01:26:12.163 --> 01:26:13.830
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN:
Chris, did you agree

01:26:13.830 --> 01:26:15.660
with Joel's presentation here?

01:26:15.660 --> 01:26:18.210
Do these models
make sense to you?

01:26:18.210 --> 01:26:22.095
[INAUDIBLE] got an interesting
story out here or--

01:26:22.095 --> 01:26:23.687
what do you think?

01:26:23.687 --> 01:26:25.270
AUDIENCE: I thought
it was interesting

01:26:25.270 --> 01:26:29.050
how he presented three
frameworks for looking

01:26:29.050 --> 01:26:31.270
at different firms,
and then went

01:26:31.270 --> 01:26:35.680
